# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: armed-forces-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] The regiment was first formed as the **105 (Scottish) Air Defence Regiment Royal Artillery** (Volunteers) on 1 April 1986 with its Regimental Headquarters at Artillery House, near Redford Barracks in Edinburgh.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] Its units were 207 (City of Glasgow) Air Defence Battery at Glasgow, 212 (Highland) Air Defence Battery at Arbroath and 218 (Lothian) Air Defence Battery at Livingston.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] It was equipped with a succession of missile systems, Blowpipe, Javelin and finally the Starstreak missile until 2005.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] In 1987 219 (City of Dundee) Air Defence Battery was formed at Dundee and joined the regiment.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] After the Options for Change defence review in 1993, 206 (Ulster) Battery transferred to the regiment from 102nd (Ulster) Air Defence Regiment.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] At that time 219 Battery disbanded and the regiment was renamed **105 Regiment Royal Artillery** (Volunteers).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] 218 Battery was disbanded in 2005 when the Regiment re-roled to field artillery.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] 105 Regiment was then equipped with the L118 105mm Light Gun.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] From 1 March 2015, the regiment has been paired with 3rd Regiment Royal Horse Artillery.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] Under Army 2020, a new battery, 278 (Lowland) Battery Royal Artillery based in Livingston joined this regiment.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/105th-regiment-royal-artillery] The battery continued the traditions of the old 278th (Lowland) Regiment (The City of Edinburgh Artillery).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The regiment was formed as the **154th (Lowland) Regiment, RCT (Volunteers)** in Glasgow in 1967.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The initially comprised just 221 Squadron and 222 Squadron.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 527 Squadron, 230 Squadron and 231 Squadron and 251 Squadron were added on amalgamation with 153 (Highland) Transport Regiment to form the **Scottish Transport Regiment** in 1993.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 231 Squadron was subsequently disbanded.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] It became **154 (Scottish) Regiment RLC** under the Army 2020 reforms and an extra squadron, 239 Squadron, was formed in 2016.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The regiment wears the Tactical Recognition Flash of the Royal Logistic Corps.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The tartan of the regiment is a version (designated "Government No.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 16") of the main MacDuff tartan, but with a smaller green area, worn by unit's pipers and drummers; in regular uniform, it is only used for the diamond-shaped cockade backing the badge on the uniform cap.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] A tartan was created in 2018 (approved in 2020) in honour of the Royal Logistic Corps, but this is for civilian use and is a fundraiser for the RLC's MOD Benevolent fund; it is not used for regimental uniform.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The **Scottish devolution referendum of 1997** was a pre-legislative referendum held in Scotland on 11 September 1997 over whether there was support for the creation of a Scottish Parliament with devolved powers, and whether the Parliament should have tax-varying powers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was "Yes–Yes": a majority voted in favour of both proposals, and the Parliament was established following an election in 1999.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The referendum was a Labour Party manifesto commitment and was held in their first term in office after the 1997 general election, under the provisions of the Referendums (Scotland and Wales) Act 1997.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was the second referendum held in Scotland over the question of devolution, the first being in 1979, and is to date the only major referendum to be held in any part of the United Kingdom where voters were asked two questions in the same plebiscite.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A referendum was held in 1979 under a Labour government which stipulated that a Scottish Assembly would come into being if the referendum had been supported by 50% of votes cast plus a controversial rule whereby at least 40% of the electorate had to vote in favour.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Although 51.6% voted in favour, this was only 32.9% of the electorate so the Assembly was not brought into being.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Shortly afterwards, the predominantly anti-devolution-led Conservative Party won the 1979 general election.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] That government put devolution to one side but it was a policy area that remained on the agenda of the Labour Party.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A Campaign for a Scottish Assembly was formed afterwards to continue the campaign.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] They brought together a committee of "prominent Scots" who drafted the document "A Claim of Right for Scotland".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "Claim" was published in 1988 and signed by most Scottish politicians, local councils, trade unions and churches.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was agreed to form a Scottish Constitutional Convention, made up of existing MPs and councillors.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party included the establishment of a Scottish Parliament in its manifesto for the 1997 general election, which they won with a landslide majority of 179.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The electorate was asked to vote on two sets of statements which corresponded to both proposals.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Scottish Labour, the SNP, Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Scottish Greens campaigned for a "Yes" vote for both proposals whilst the Scottish Conservatives opposed both proposals.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Labour MP Tam Dalyell opposed the creation of the Parliament, but accepted that it should have tax-varying powers if it were to be established.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The official Yes campaign, *Scotland Forward* (styled "Scotland FORward"), was headed by the businessman Nigel Smith and came out of the groups that had previously formed the Scottish Constitutional Convention, along with the Scottish National Party.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was supported by the Labour, SNP, Liberal Democrat and Green parties.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The official No campaign, *Think Twice*, was headed by Brian Monteith, a former employee of the Conservative MP Michael Forsyth.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Board members included Donald Findlay, rector of the University of St Andrews and vice-chairman of Rangers F.C., and senior Conservative peer Lord Fraser.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, it struggled to get much business support as they were wary of opposing a project that had such support from the new government which had a large majority.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Campaigning in the referendum was suspended between the death and funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was speculated that the Scottish referendum could have been postponed, but this would have required a recall of the UK Parliament and an amendment to the Referendums Act.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was "Yes-Yes": the majority voted "I agree" in favour of both proposals.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Two council areas had an overall "Yes-No" result – Dumfries and Galloway and Orkney.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] More votes were cast for the first question than the second in all regions (except Fife), with substantially more spoilt ballots for the second question, perhaps due to voter confusion over the two papers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Votes in favour of tax-varying powers still commanded significant majority, when compared to establishing the Parliament per se.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A majority voted 'I agree' in every local council, apart from in Dumfries & Galloway and Orkney.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] In response to the majority voting for "Yes" to both proposals, the UK Parliament passed the Scotland Act 1998.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] This established a Scottish Parliament for the first time since the adjournment of the pre-Union Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The devolved Parliament convened for the first time in May 1999, following its first election.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was a poll that the Conservative Party had to fight despite losing their "No" Campaign and having no Westminster seats in Scotland after losing the 1997 general election.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Scotland Act 1998 also created the Scottish Executive, later to become known as the Scottish Government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Professor Tom Devine, academic at the University of Edinburgh, dubbed the referendum result "the most significant development in Scottish political history since the Union of 1707".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Prime Minister Tony Blair claimed that "the era of big centralised government is over".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "Yes" campaign leaders Donald Dewar (Scottish Labour) and Alex Salmond (Scottish National Party) held different views over the devolution proposal.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, they put their political differences aside immediately after the vote in celebration.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Despite this, the SNP's calls for independence soon reignited with SNP leader Alex Salmond claiming that there would be an independent Scotland within his lifetime.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "No" campaign did not share this optimism and feared that this vote was a catalyst towards the break-up of the Union.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Detail was also lacking in that the Scottish Constitutional Convention had failed to address issues such as the role of The Queen or aspects of tax-varying powers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] 19th Regiment traces its history to 17 Brigade Royal Field Artillery which was formed in 1900 but the individual batteries date back to the 18th century.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] The brigade saw action during World War I.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] During World War II, the four pre-war batteries combined into two.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] In May 1940 it had the honour of being the first artillery regiment to fire in the war while stationed at the Maginot Line.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] It served during the North African and Italian campaigns.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] The regiment was renumbered to 19 Regiment in 1947.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] During the 1950s and 1960s it served in the Korean War and Aden Emergency.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] With the phasing out of National Service in 1963, 19th Regiment was allocated the recruitment area of the Scottish Highlands.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] In 1995, the regiment was deployed to Bosnia at short notice as part of Operation Deliberate Force.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] It was deployed to Cyprus in 1998 as part of UNFICYP.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] Since the 2000s, it has served in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] More recently, the regiment returned from Afghanistan (Op Herrick 16) in October 2012.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] In December 2012, the regiment was officially named "The Scottish Gunners" when the 40th Regiment Royal Artillery (The Lowland Gunners) was placed in suspended animation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] 38 (Seringapatam) Battery was transferred to 19th Regt.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] A new banner for the Pipes and Drums was presented and a plaque unveiled at the regiment's barracks to mark the occasion.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] In 2019, the regiment was due to move within Wiltshire from Bhurtpore Barracks at Tidworth to new purpose-built barracks at Larkhill.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] As part of the Future Soldier Programme, the regiment joined the new 3rd Deep Reconnaissance Strike Brigade on 1 July 2022.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] In addition the regiment restructured in 2023, gaining 19 (Gibraltar 1779-83) Battery from 26th Regiment, RA as an Ajax equipped Tactical Group Battery.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] The regiment traditionally recruited from the Highlands as its former nickname suggested but now also recruits from Grampian, Tayside, Fife, central Scotland and Argyll.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] With 40 Regt "Lowland Gunners" being placed into suspended animation as part of the Army 2020 plans, it became the principal Scottish artillery regiment.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] 19 Regiment RA is the local artillery regiment of the Highlands of Scotland, the Western Isles, Shetland and Orkney.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] The Regiment has been granted the Freedoms of the Cities of Inverness and Colchester.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] Bandsmen of the unit wear the hunting Robertson tartan in their dress uniforms (kilts and full plaids).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/19th-regiment-royal-artillery] This tartan was inherited from the original Loyal Clan Donnachie Volunteers raised in 1803, a unit of irregulars raised on Clan Robertson–Donnachaidh–Duncan lands.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The **Ranger Regiment** is a special operations-capable regiment of the British Army which was formed on 1 December 2021 under the Future Soldier reform and is part of the Army Special Operations Brigade previously called the Specialised Infantry Group.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] It is intended to be used primarily in an unconventional warfare and foreign internal defence capacity in a similar manner to the US Army Special Forces.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] On 22 March 2021, the Defence in a Competitive Age paper was released underlining the future of the British Armed Forces.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] Initially, the regiment is planned to be "based on four Infantry Battalions but selecting personnel from across the Army".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The regiment's task will be as follows: "[It will be] designed to support and conduct special operations discreetly in high-risk environments".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] According to a reporter of Forces News, the regiment will "conduct missions traditionally carried out by United Kingdom Special Forces (Special Air Service and Special Boat Service)".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] During an interview with the (then) Chief of the Defence Staff, General Sir Nick Carter, the rangers will be "special forces" and will "go beyond training, advising, and assisting" to "support local operations".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] He also stated the Ranger's functions will be similar to the United States Army's "Green Berets", a nickname for the US Army Special Forces.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The regiment was initially due to form in August 2021, but this was subsequently postponed to 1 December 2021.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] In early 2022 soldiers from the regiment deployed as part of a UK government support package to Ukraine.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] In February 2022 soldiers from the regiment deployed to Ghana to conduct training with the Ghanaian Special Operations Brigade, in preparation for a major exercise as well as to help them eliminate threats originating from their border regions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] After it was revealed to the public, some army officers were concerned that the cap badge of the Ranger Regiment bore a resemblance to the badge of the Selous Scouts, a special forces unit of the Rhodesian Army which operated during the Rhodesian Bush War.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The British Army rejected the claims, stating that the badge was designed around the peregrine falcon, not the osprey in the Selous Scouts’ cap badge.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] Elements of the Ranger Regiment deployed to Ukraine in 2022 to provide anti-tank training.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] In October 2022 elements of the 3rd Battalion conducted exercises with the 193rd Jägarbataljonen, part of the Norrland Dragoon Regiment, specialised arctic light infantry.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] In March 2024, the Armed Forces Minister, James Heappey, said that the Ranger Regiment had deployed 691 times since 2021 and that, as of 1 January 2024, it consisted of 1,040 regular Army personnel.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The regiment was formed on 1 December 2021 through the renaming of four of the existing Specialised Infantry battalions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] All four battalions were formed on 1 December 2021 and fall under the Army Special Operations Brigade, operationally they are aligned to regions around the globe.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] A gun-metal grey beret and stable belt are worn by the Regiment.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The four battalions of the Ranger Regiment each consist of ≈ 250 personnel.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The 1st Battalion, Ranger Regiment (1 RANGER) was formed by the personnel of the disbanded Royal Scots Borderers, 1st Battalion, Royal Regiment of Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The battalion is based at Palace Barracks in Belfast, Northern Ireland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] It is regionally aligned to Southern Europe.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The 2nd Battalion, Ranger Regiment (2 RANGER) was formed by the personnel of the disbanded 2nd Battalion, Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment (Queen's and Royal Hampshires).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The battalion is based at Keogh Barracks, Ash Vale, Surrey.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The 3rd Battalion, Ranger Regiment (3 RANGER) was formed by the personnel of the disbanded 2nd Battalion, Duke of Lancaster's Regiment (King's, Lancashire and Border).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The battalion is currently based at Elizabeth Barracks, Pirbright, but will move to Keogh Barracks in 2027.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] It is regionally aligned to Northern Europe.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The 4th Battalion, Ranger Regiment (4 RANGER) was formed by the personnel of the disbanded 4th Battalion, The Rifles.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The battalion is based at Normandy Barracks, Aldershot Garrison.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] It is regionally aligned to the Middle East and Indo-Pacific.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The regiment also includes a trio of Gurkha reinforcement companies.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] These were raised as part of the plan to reform the 3rd Battalion, Royal Gurkha Rifles, which would be the fifth battalion assigned to the Specialised Infantry Group.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] A (Coriano) Company was formed on 31 January 2020 as the first sub-unit of the new battalion.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The formation of the new battalion's second company was planned for 18 November 2021, but prior to this taking place, the formation of the new battalion was cancelled, with the two companies instead to be used as independent units attached to other battalions of the new Ranger Regiment.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] Upon the formation of the Rangers, the second formed company, F (Falklands) Company, was attached to 2 RANGER, while the original company, renamed as G (Coriano) Company, was attached to 4 RANGER.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] A third company, A (Krithia) Company, was formed in September 2024, to operate as part of 1 RANGER, becoming the first Gurkha unit to be stationed in Northern Ireland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The Ranger Regiment is organised into "teams" of 11 personnel similar to United States Army Special Forces ODAs, which consist of 12 soldiers, each of whom has a particular specialist role.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] The Ranger battalions were planned to be "all-arms" battalions and thus be open to anyone serving in the Army, providing that they have served for 18 months from completing basic training.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] All applicants to the ranger regiment have to undertake a two-week Ranger assessment cadre (RAC), followed by a ten week All Arms Ranger course (AARC) before joining their battalion.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/1st-battalion-ranger-regiment-united-kingdom] Brigadier Gus Fair, then commander of the Ranger Regiment, said the RAC involves "protracted periods of time under duress" and seeks to select applicants with emotional intelligence, resilience, calmness and self-awareness.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A referendum on Scottish independence from the United Kingdom was held in Scotland on 18 September 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The referendum question was "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which voters answered with "Yes" or "No".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The turnout of 84.6% was the highest recorded for an election or referendum in the United Kingdom since the January 1910 general election, which was held before the introduction of universal suffrage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 set out the arrangements for the referendum and was passed by the Scottish Parliament in November 2013, following an agreement between the devolved Scottish government and the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The independence proposal required a simple majority to pass.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] All European Union (EU) or Commonwealth citizens residing in Scotland age 16 or over could vote, with some exceptions, which produced a total electorate of almost 4,300,000 people.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was the first time that the electoral franchise was extended to include 16- and 17-year-olds in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Yes Scotland was the main campaign group for independence, while Better Together was the main campaign group in favour of maintaining the union.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Many other campaign groups, political parties, businesses, newspapers, and prominent individuals were also involved.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Prominent issues raised during the referendum included what currency an independent Scotland would use, public expenditure, EU membership, and North Sea oil.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An exit poll revealed that retention of the pound sterling was the deciding factor for those who voted No, while "disaffection with Westminster politics" was the deciding factor for those who voted Yes.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England were established as independent countries during the Middle Ages.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After fighting a series of wars during the 14th century, the two monarchies entered a personal union in 1603 (the Union of the Crowns) when James VI of Scotland also became James I of England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two nations were temporarily united under one government when Oliver Cromwell was declared Lord Protector of a Commonwealth in 1653, but this was dissolved when the monarchy was restored in 1660.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Scotland and England united to form the Kingdom of Great Britain in 1707 (Wales had already been unilaterally incorporated into England in the mid-16th century).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scots favoured union to solve the economic problems caused by the failure of the Darien scheme and the English favoured it to secure the Hanoverian line of succession.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Great Britain in turn united with the Kingdom of Ireland in 1801, forming the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Most of Ireland left the Union in 1922 to form the Irish Free State; consequently, the full name of the United Kingdom since 1927 is the *United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland*.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Labour Party was committed to home rule for Scotland in the 1920s, but it slipped down its agenda in the following years.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish National Party (SNP) was founded in 1934, but did not achieve significant electoral success until the 1960s.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A petition calling for home rule, the Scottish Covenant, was signed by 2,000,000 people (out of a population of 5,000,000) in the late 1940s.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As James Callaghan's Labour Government of the late 1970s was pressured by the SNP, Scottish devolution was, for the first time, seriously proposed.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In a 1979 referendum for a devolved Scottish Assembly, a narrow majority of votes were cast in favour of devolution, but this had no effect due to a requirement that the number voting 'Yes' had to exceed 40% of the total electorate.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] No further constitutional reform was proposed until Labour returned to power in a landslide electoral victory in May 1997.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A second Scottish devolution referendum was held later that year, as promised in the Labour election manifesto.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Clear majorities expressed support for both a devolved Scottish Parliament (74.3% in favour) and that Parliament having the power to vary the basic rate of UK income tax (63.5% in favour).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scotland Act 1998 established the new Scottish Parliament, first elected on 6 May 1999, with power to legislate on unreserved matters within Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A commitment to hold an independence referendum in 2010 was part of the SNP's election manifesto when it contested the 2007 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The press were largely hostile towards the SNP, with a headline for *The Scottish Sun* in May 2007 stating – beside an image of a hangman's noose – "Vote SNP today and you put Scotland's head in the noose".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As a result of that election, the SNP became the largest party in the Scottish Parliament and formed a minority government led by the First Minister, Alex Salmond.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP administration launched a 'National Conversation' as a consultation exercise in August 2007, part of which included a draft referendum bill, the *Referendum (Scotland) Bill*.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After this, a white paper for the proposed Referendum Bill was published, on 30 November 2009.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It detailed four possible scenarios, with the text of the Bill and Referendum to be revealed later.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The scenarios were: no change; devolution per the Calman Review; further devolution; and full independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government published a draft version of the bill on 25 February 2010 for public consultation; *Scotland's Future: Draft Referendum (Scotland) Bill Consultation Paper* contained a consultation document and a draft version of the bill.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The consultation paper set out the proposed ballot papers, the mechanics of the proposed referendum, and how the proposed referendum was to be regulated.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The third proposal was for full independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 3rd Scottish Parliament only 50 of 129 MSPs (47 SNP, 2 Greens, and Margo MacDonald) supported a referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government withdrew the bill in September 2010 after failing to secure opposition support.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP repeated its commitment to hold an independence referendum when it published its manifesto for the 2011 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Days before the election, Salmond said that legislation for a referendum would be proposed in the "second half of the parliament", as he wanted to secure more powers for the Scottish Parliament via the Scotland Bill first.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the election, the SNP won 69 of the 129 seats, securing a majority in a proportional representative voting system.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] UK Prime Minister David Cameron congratulated Salmond on his 'emphatic win', but pledged to campaign for the Union if the SNP carried out their pledge to hold a referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, the UK government offered to legislate to provide the Scottish Parliament with the powers to hold a referendum, providing it was 'fair, legal and decisive'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This would set 'terms of reference for the referendum', such as its question(s), elector eligibility, and which body would organise the vote.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As the UK government worked on legal details, including the timing of the vote, Salmond announced an intention to hold the referendum in the autumn of 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Negotiations continued between the two governments until October 2012, when the Edinburgh Agreement was reached.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum (Franchise) Act 2013 was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 27 June 2013 and received Royal Assent on 7 August 2013.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 26 November 2013, the Scottish government published *Scotland's Future*, a 670-page white paper laying out the case for independence and the means by which Scotland might become an independent country.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Government announced on 21 March 2013 that the referendum would be held on Thursday 18 September 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Some media reports mentioned that 2014 would be the 700th anniversary of the Battle of Bannockburn and that Scotland would also host the 2014 Commonwealth Games and the 2014 Ryder Cup.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond agreed that the presence of these events made 2014 a "good year to hold a referendum".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Convicted prisoners were not able to vote in the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) had ruled that this restriction was unlawful, but Scottish judge Lord Glennie said that he believed the ECHR judgment would apply only to parliamentary elections.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Appeals against his ruling were rejected by the Court of Session in Edinburgh and the UK Supreme Court.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The normal voting age was reduced from 18 to 16 for the referendum, as it was a Scottish National Party policy to reduce the voting age for all elections in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The move was supported by Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the Scottish Greens.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, Labour MSP Elaine Murray led a debate arguing that the franchise should be extended to Scots living outside Scotland, including the approximately 800,000 living in the other parts of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the House of Lords, Baroness Symons argued that the rest of the UK should be allowed to vote on Scottish independence because it would affect the whole country.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This argument was rejected by the UK government, as the Advocate General for Scotland Lord Wallace said that "whether or not Scotland should leave the United Kingdom is a matter for Scotland".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Wallace also pointed to the fact that only two of 11 referendums since 1973 had been across all of the United Kingdom.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Professor John Curtice cited the precedent of the 1973 Northern Ireland sovereignty referendum (the "border poll"), which allowed only those resident in a part of the UK to vote on its sovereignty.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was debate as to whether the Scottish Parliament had the power to legislate for a referendum relating to the issue of Scottish independence, as the constitution is a matter reserved to the UK Parliament.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government insisted in 2010 that they could legislate for a referendum, as it would be an "advisory referendum on extending the powers of the Scottish Parliament", whose result would "have no legal effect on the Union".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Lord Wallace, Advocate General for Scotland, said in January 2012 that holding a referendum concerning the constitution would be outside the legislative power of the Scottish Parliament and that private individuals could challenge a Scottish Parliament referendum bill.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two governments signed the Edinburgh Agreement, which allowed for the temporary transfer of legal authority.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Per the Edinburgh Agreement, the UK government drafted an Order in Council granting the Scottish Parliament the necessary powers to hold, on or before 31 December 2014, an independence referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The draft Order was approved by resolutions of both Houses of Parliament, and the Order ("The Scotland Act 1998 (Modification of Schedule 5) Order 2013"), was approved by Queen Elizabeth II at a meeting of the Privy Council on 12 February 2013.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under the powers temporarily transferred from Westminster under the section 30 Order, the Scottish Parliament adopted the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Act was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 14 November 2013 and received Royal Assent on 17 December 2013.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under section 36 of the Act, it came into force the day after Royal Assent.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission was responsible for overseeing the referendum, "with the exception of the conduct of the poll and announcement of the result, and the giving of grants.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In its role of regulating the campaign and campaign spending, the Electoral Commission will report to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] (...) The poll and count will be managed in the same way as [local] elections, by local returning officers (...) and directed by a Chief Counting Officer".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Edinburgh Agreement stated that the wording of the question would be decided by the Scottish Parliament and reviewed for intelligibility by the Electoral Commission.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government stated that its preferred question was "Do you agree that Scotland should be an independent country?" The Electoral Commission tested the proposed question along with three other possible versions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Their research found that the "Do you agree" preface made it a leading question, which would be more likely to garner a positive response.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The question was amended to "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which the Electoral Commission found was the most neutral and concise of the versions tested.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 2010 Draft Bill, the Scottish government proposed that there would be one designated campaign organisation for each outcome, both of which would be permitted to spend up to £750,000 on their campaign and to send one free mailshot to every household or voter in the referendum franchise.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was to be no public funding for campaigns.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Registered political parties were each to be allowed to spend £100,000.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This proposed limit on party spending was increased to £250,000 in 2012.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In 2013, new proposals by the Electoral Commission for the 16-week regulated period preceding the poll were accepted.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] They allowed the two designated campaign organisations to spend up to £1.5 million each and for the parties in Scotland to spend the following amounts: £1,344,000 (SNP); £834,000 (Labour); £396,000 (Conservatives); £201,000 (Liberal Democrats); £150,000 (Greens).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An unlimited number of other organisations could register with the Electoral Commission, but their spending was limited to £150,000.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Groups spending more than £250,000 were required to submit audited returns to the Commission by 18 March 2015.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] According to the Scottish government's consultation paper published on 25 February 2010, the cost of the referendum was "likely to be around £9.5 million", mostly spent on running the poll and the count.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Costs would also include the posting of one neutral information leaflet about the referendum to every Scottish household, and one free mailshot to every household or voter in the poll for the designated campaign organisations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In April 2013, the projected cost of the referendum was £13.3 million; the final administrative cost was £15.85 million.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scottish independence, Yes Scotland, was launched on 25 May 2012.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Its chief executive was Blair Jenkins, formerly the Director of Broadcasting at STV and Head of News and Current Affairs at both STV and BBC Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign was supported by the SNP, the Scottish Green Party (which also created "its own pro-independence campaign to run alongside Yes Scotland") and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] At its launch, Salmond stated that he hoped one million people in Scotland would sign a declaration of support for independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 22 August 2014, Yes Scotland announced that the one million target had been surpassed.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scotland remaining in the UK, Better Together, was launched on 25 June 2012.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was led by Alistair Darling, former Chancellor of the Exchequer, and had support from the Conservative Party, Labour Party and Liberal Democrats.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Political advertising on television and radio in the UK was prohibited by the Communications Act 2003, with the exception of permitted party political broadcasts.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Three major cinema chains stopped showing adverts by referendum campaign groups after receiving negative feedback from their customers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In December 2013, the Better Together campaign declared that it had received donations of £2,800,000.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Six-figure contributions were made by businessmen Ian Taylor and Donald Houston, and by author C.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Almost 27,000 donations of under £7,500 had been received by the same date.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Rowling, who announced in June 2014 that she had given £1,000,000 to the Better Together campaign.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the following month, whisky distiller William Grant & Sons announced a donation of approximately £100,000.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 12 August 2014, Better Together announced that it had raised enough money to cover the maximum spending permitted and was no longer accepting donations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was attributed in part to a large number of small donations being received after the first televised debate between First Minister Alex Salmond and Labour MP Alistair Darling.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of May 2014, the Yes Scotland campaign had declared £4,500,000 in cash donations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] EuroMillions lottery-winners Chris and Colin Weir gave £3,500,000.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A six-figure donation was given by investment fund manager Angus Tulloch; approximately 18,000 donations of less than £7,500 had been made by the same date.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Voting for the referendum commenced on 27 August 2014, with the receipt of ballots by postal voters.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of 15 August, 680,235 eligible voters had registered for postal voting, a 20% increase compared with March 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] During the postal vote phase, Police Scotland arrested a man from Glasgow on suspicion of selling his vote on eBay.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The registration deadline for referendum voters was 2 September 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Several councils reported the processing of "unprecedented" numbers of new registrations, while others received "tens of thousands" of applications in the final week.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The UK Government said that, if a simple majority of the vote was in favour of independence, then 'Scotland would become an independent country after a process of negotiations'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] If the majority opposed independence, Scotland would remain part of the United Kingdom.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Further powers would be devolved to the Scottish Parliament as a result of the Scotland Act 2012.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission prepared an information leaflet which confirmed that the UK and Scottish governments had reached agreement on these points.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Cameron said in May 2014 that he believed that the referendum would be 'irreversible and binding'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the week before the referendum, both sides said they would abide by the result.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond said that it was a 'once in a generation' event, citing the precedent of the two devolution referendums in 1979 and 1997.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the event of a majority for Yes, the Scottish Government had proposed an independence date of 24 March 2016.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was suggested that, after negotiations concluded, the UK Parliament would legislate for Scottish independence to take place on the date that had been negotiated.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A report by a UK House of Lords committee published in May 2014 said that the UK could opt to delay the independence date.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, as part of a European Union (EU) member state, Scottish farmers received £583 million in subsidy payments from the EU under the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Annual CAP payments are made to the UK, which then determines how much to allocate to each of the devolved administrations, including Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the last CAP agreement, farmers in the UK qualified for additional convergence payments because Scottish farmers received a lower average single farm payment per hectare, mainly due to the mountainous terrain in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence therefore believed that an independent Scotland would receive greater agricultural subsidies as an independent state.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Opponents of independence believed that Scottish farmers benefited from the Union because the UK was one of the larger EU member states, and therefore had a greater say in CAP negotiations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] They also questioned whether an independent Scotland would immediately receive full subsidy payments from the EU, as recent new member states had their subsidies phased in.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the independence referendum, the UK had some opt-outs from EU policies.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] One was the opt-out from the Schengen Area, meaning there were full passport checks for travellers from other EU countries except the Republic of Ireland, which was part of a Common Travel Area (CTA) with the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that an independent Scotland would remain outside the Schengen Area and remain inside the CTA, ensuring that no passport controls would be needed at the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon commented that an independent Scotland would negotiate with the EU to have the same visa arrangements as the UK has.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Carmichael, the Secretary of State for Scotland, said in January 2014 that it would make sense for Scotland to be in the CTA, but it would have to operate similar immigration policies to the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This position was supported by Home Secretary Theresa May, who said in March 2014 that passport checks should be introduced if Scotland adopted a looser immigration policy.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Conservative MP Richard Bacon said there would be "no reason" for border controls to be implemented.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the white paper *Scotland's Future*, the Scottish government pledged to expand childcare provision in an independent Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The paper stated that this policy would cost £700 million, but that this would be financed by increased tax revenue from an additional 100,000 women returning to work.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In March 2014, the National Day Nurseries Association said that the plan could not be implemented unless greater funding was provided by local authorities to private nurseries.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Scottish Parliament Information Centre questioned the economic benefit of the policy, pointing out that there were only 64,000 mothers of children aged between 1 and 5 who were economically inactive.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that all British citizens who had been born in Scotland would automatically become Scottish citizens on the date of independence, regardless of whether or not they were then living in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] British citizens "habitually resident" in Scotland would also be considered Scottish citizens, even if they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Every person who would automatically be considered a Scottish citizen would be able to opt-out of Scottish citizenship provided they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] UK Home Secretary Theresa May said the future policies of an independent Scottish government would affect whether Scottish citizens would be allowed to retain British citizenship.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] An analysis paper published by the UK government in January 2014 stated that it was likely that Scots would be able to hold dual citizenship; however, the duality was considered for all other countries, not specifically to the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The possibility of holding dual UK–Scotland citizenships could be subject to the "proof of affinity".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A YouGov poll in early September showed 25 per cent of the electorate believed MI5 was working with the British government to block independence, with many voters so fearful that the marks made by the pencils provided in polling stations would be tampered with that they brought their own pens.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP said that there was a defence underspend of 'at least £7.4 billion' between 2002 and 2012 in Scotland and that independence would allow the Scottish government to correct this imbalance.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In its white paper, the Scottish government planned that an independent Scotland would have a total of 15,000 regular and 5,000 reserve personnel across land, air and maritime forces by 2026.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In July 2013, the SNP proposed that there would be a £2.5 billion annual military budget in an independent Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons Defence Select Committee said that the £2.5bn budget was too low.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Andrew Murrison, UK Minister for International Security Strategy agreed and said it was 'risible' for the SNP to suggest it could create an independent force by 'salami-slicing' from current British armed forces units.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons defence committee also stated that Scottish independence would have a negative effect on its industry, while the UK government said it would not be willing to build warships in a foreign country.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The chief executive of Thales, one of Britain's largest defence suppliers, said that if Scotland became independent that this might raise questions about continued investment from his firm.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Royal United Services Institute said in 2012 that an independent Scotland could set up a Scottish Defence Force, comparable in size and strength to those of other small European states like Denmark, Norway, and Ireland, at an annual cost of £1.8 billion.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Dorcha Lee, a former colonel in the Irish Army, said that Scotland could eschew forming an army based on inherited resources from the British Army and instead follow an Irish model of a limited self-defence force.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the referendum, the Trident nuclear missile system was based at Coulport weapons depot and naval base of Faslane in the Firth of Clyde area.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP objected to having nuclear weapons on Scottish territory, but British military leaders said that there was no alternative site for the missiles.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In April 2014, several British military leaders co-signed a letter stating that forcing Trident to leave Scottish waters would place the UK nuclear deterrent in jeopardy.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] *Nowhere to Go*, a report by Scottish CND, concluded that the removal of Trident from Scotland would force unilateral nuclear disarmament by the United Kingdom, as the weapons would have no viable alternative base.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Royal United Services Institute said that relocating Trident would be 'very difficult, but not impossible' and estimated it would take about 10 years and create an additional cost of around £3 billion.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] According to a seminar hosted by the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, that the Royal Navy would have to consider a range of alternatives, including disarmament.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A 2013 Scotland Institute report suggested a future Scottish government could be convinced to lease the Faslane nuclear base to the rest of the UK, in order to maintain good diplomatic relations and expedite NATO entry negotiations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] SNP policy had historically been that an independent Scotland should not seek to obtain membership in NATO, but this was dropped after a vote by party members in 2012.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] MSPs John Finnie and Jean Urquhart resigned from the SNP over this policy change.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party and Scottish Socialist Party continued their opposition to NATO membership.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP position that Trident nuclear weapons should be removed from Scotland but that it should hold NATO membership was criticised by Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Patrick Harvie, co-convenor of the Scottish Green Party.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Malcolm Chalmers of the Royal United Services Institute said that 'pragmatists' in the SNP accepted that NATO membership would likely involve a long-term basing deal, enabling the UK to keep Trident on the Clyde.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was disputed by Mariot Leslie, a former UK permanent representative to NATO, who said that NATO would not want to disrupt its arrangements by excluding Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A UK government paper on security said that Police Scotland would lose access to the UK intelligence apparatus, including MI5, SIS, and GCHQ, and that an independent Scottish state would need to build security infrastructure.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Theresa May commented that an independent Scotland would have access to less security capability, but would not necessarily face a reduced threat.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] May also indicated that the British government would block Scotland from joining the Five Eyes intelligence-sharing alliance until Scotland had built up its own spying and intelligence infrastructure and was able to offer the alliance a "unique contribution".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Allan Burnett, former head of intelligence with Strathclyde Police and Scotland's counter-terrorism coordinator until 2010, said that 'an independent Scotland would face less of a threat, intelligence institutions will be readily created, and allies will remain allies'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Baroness Ramsay, a Labour peer and former case officer with MI6, said that the Scottish government's stance on intelligence was 'extremely naïve' and that it was "not going to be as simple as they think".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon said that Scotland would create a security service like MI5 to work alongside police and tackle terrorism, cyber-attacks and serious organised crime, and that creating an external intelligence agency would remain an option.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government and pro-independence campaigners said there was a democratic deficit in Scotland because the UK was a unitary state without a codified constitution.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP also called the unelected House of Lords an 'affront to democracy'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The 'democratic deficit' label has sometimes been used to refer to the period between the 1979 and 1997 UK general elections, during which the Labour Party held a majority of Scottish seats but the Conservative Party governed the whole of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in September 2013 that instances such as this amounted to a lack of democracy, and that 'people who live and work in Scotland are the people most likely to make the right choices for Scotland'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Menzies Campbell wrote in April 2014 that any democratic deficit had been addressed by creating the devolved Scottish Parliament, and that 'Scotland and the Scottish have enjoyed influence beyond our size or reasonable expectation' within the British government and the wider political system.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Conservative MP Daniel Kawczynski said in 2009 that the UK's asymmetric devolution had created a democratic deficit for England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was commonly known as the West Lothian question, which cited the anomaly whereby English MPs could not vote on affairs devolved to Scotland but Scottish MPs could vote on the equivalent subjects in England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Kawczynski also pointed out that the average number of voters in a parliamentary constituency was larger in England than in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the campaign, each of the three main UK parties conducted reviews of the UK constitution, with each recommending that more powers should devolve to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On the morning before a televised debate between Alex Salmond and Alistair Darling, Better Together published a joint statement.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Co-signed by the three main UK party leaders (David Cameron, Ed Miliband and Nick Clegg), it committed to granting Scotland increased power over domestic taxes and parts of the social security system.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Boris Johnson, the Conservative mayor of London, said he opposed giving the Scottish Parliament greater fiscal powers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the second televised debate, Salmond challenged Darling to specify which additional powers that could help create greater employment in Scotland would be granted if there was a 'no' vote.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During a visit to Scotland later that week, David Cameron promised more powers 'soon'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 8 September, former Prime Minister Gordon Brown suggested a timetable for the additional powers to be implemented in the event of a 'no' vote.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He proposed that work on a new Scotland Act would begin immediately after the referendum, resulting in the publication of a white paper by the end of November 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Two days before the referendum, the three main UK party leaders publicly pledged to introduce 'extensive new powers' by the timetable suggested and that the Barnett formula of public funding would continue.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A principal issue in the referendum was the economy.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Weir Group, one of the largest private companies based in Scotland, commissioned a study by Oxford Economics into the potential economic effects of Scottish independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It found that Weir would pay more corporation tax, despite the Scottish government's proposal to cut the rate of corporation tax, due to it no longer being able to offset losses in Scotland against profits in the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It also stated that independence would result in additional costs and complexity in the operation of business pension schemes.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report found that 70% of all Scottish exports are sold to the rest of the UK, which it said would particularly affect the financial services sector.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Standard Life, one of the Scottish financial sector's largest businesses, said in February 2014 that it had started registering companies in England in case it had to relocate some of its operations there.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In February 2014, the *Financial Times* noted that Scotland's per capita GDP was bigger than that of France when a geographic share of oil and gas was taken into account, and still bigger than that of Italy when it was not.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] As of April 2014, Scotland had a similar rate of unemployment to the UK average (6.6%) and a lower fiscal deficit (including as a percentage of GDP).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scotland performed better than the UK average in securing new Foreign Direct Investment in 2012–13 (measured by the number of projects), although not as well as Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] GDP growth during 2013 was lower in Scotland than in the rest of the UK, although this was partly due to an industrial dispute at the Grangemouth Refinery.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Deutsche Bank issued a report in the week before the referendum in which David Folkerts-Landau, the bank's chief economist, concluded: 'While it may sound simple and costless for a nation to exit a 300-year-old union, nothing could be further from the truth'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Folkerts-Landau said the economic prospects after a 'yes' vote were 'incomprehensible', and cited Winston Churchill's 1925 Gold Standard decision and the actions of America's Federal Reserve that triggered the Great Depression of the 1930s as mistakes of a similar magnitude.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Swiss financial services company UBS supported Deutsche Bank's position.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence said that Scotland had not realised its full economic potential because it was subject to the same economic policy as the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation published a report stating that UK economic policy had become 'overwhelmingly geared to helping London, meaning Scotland and other UK regions suffer from being denied the specific, local policies they need'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Later in January 2014, Colin Fox said that Scotland is 'penalised by an economic model biased towards the South East of England'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In November 2013, Chic Brodie said that Scotland was deprived of economic benefit in the 1980s after the Ministry of Defence blocked oil exploration off the West of Scotland, ostensibly to avoid interference with the UK's nuclear weapons arsenal.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Treasury issued a report on 20 May 2013 which said that Scotland's banking systems would be too big to ensure depositor compensation in the event of a bank failure.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report indicated that Scottish banks would have assets worth 1,254% of GDP, which was more than Cyprus and Iceland before the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It suggested Scottish taxpayers would each have £65,000 of potential liabilities during a hypothetical bailout in Scotland, versus £30,000 as part of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Economists including Andrew Hughes Hallett, Professor of Economics at St Andrews University, rejected the idea that Scotland would have to underwrite these liabilities alone.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He observed that banks operating in more than one country can be given a joint bailout by multiple governments.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In this way, France, Belgium, and the Netherlands collectively bailed out Fortis Bank and the Dexia Bank.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The American Federal Reserve System lent more than $1 trillion to British banks, including $446 billion to the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), because they had operations in the United States.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Robert Peston reported in March 2014 that RBS and Lloyds Banking Group might be forced to relocate their head offices from Edinburgh to London in case of Scottish independence, due to a European law brought in after the 1991 collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Financial groups including RBS, Lloyds, Clydesdale Bank, TSB, and Tesco Bank later announced that they planned to move their registered headquarters from Scotland to England if Scotland voted for independence, although most indicated that they had no immediate intention to transfer any jobs.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Another major economic issue was the currency that an independent Scotland would use.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The principal options were to establish an independent Scottish currency, join the euro, or retain the pound sterling (a form of currency substitution).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Throughout the 1990s and early 2000s, the SNP's policy was that an independent Scotland should adopt the euro, though this was relegated to a long-term rather than short-term goal by the party's 2009 conference.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] There was disagreement over whether Scotland would be required to join the euro if it became an EU member state in its own right.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] All new members are required to commit to joining the single currency, but they must first be party to ERM II for two years.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government argued that this was a *de facto* opt-out from the euro, because EU member states are not obliged to join ERM II.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] For example, the people of Sweden rejected adopting the euro in a 2003 referendum and its government subsequently refused to enter ERM II.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP favoured continued use of sterling in an independent Scotland through a formal currency union with the UK, with the Bank of England setting its interest rates and monetary policy and acting as its central bank.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In June 2012, Alistair Darling said voters in the rest of the UK could choose not to be in a currency union with Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Sir John Major rejected the idea of a currency union, saying it would require the UK to underwrite Scottish debt.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Gordon Brown said the SNP proposal would create a 'colonial relationship' between Scotland and Westminster.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones said in November 2013 that he would seek a veto on a currency union between Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Yes Scotland said that a currency union would benefit both Scotland and the rest of the UK, as Scotland's exports would boost the balance of payments, and consequently strengthen the exchange rate of sterling.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Meanwhile, UK economists and financial experts said the effect on the balance of payments and the exchange rate would be 'largely neutral'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Sterling fell by almost one cent against the US dollar in a day early in September 2014, due to an opinion poll showing a swing towards the Yes campaign.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The *Financial Times* reported a few days later that 'Asset managers, investors and pension savers are moving billions of pounds out of Scotland' because of fears that Scotland would leave the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The newspaper also reported that '"exit clauses" are being inserted into commercial property contracts in Scotland to allow buyers to scrap deals or renegotiate prices if voters opt for independence'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scottish Labour leader Johann Lamont said that any additional transaction costs would fall largely on Scottish companies, costing businesses in Scotland 11 times more than those in England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute of Directors said that any new transaction costs would 'pale in comparison to the financial danger of entering an unstable currency union'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Banking experts said that being the 'junior partner' in a currency arrangement could amount to 'a loss of fiscal autonomy for Scotland' if policy constraints were imposed on the Scottish state.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Angus Armstrong of the National Institute of Economic and Social Research wrote that the implicit constraints on its economic policy would be more restrictive than the explicit ones it faced as part of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in February 2014 that an independent Scotland in a currency union would retain tax and spending powers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Chancellor George Osborne, as well as equivalent post-holders in the two other main UK political parties, rejected the idea of a formal currency union with an independent Scotland in February 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Shadow Chancellor Ed Balls said the SNP's proposals for a currency union were 'economically incoherent' and that any currency option for an independent Scotland would be 'less advantageous than what we have across the UK today'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] After the three main UK political parties ruled out a formal currency union, the Adam Smith Institute said that the economies of Panama, Ecuador, and El Salvador 'demonstrate that the informal use of another country's currency can foster a healthy financial system and economy'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In September 2014, former European Commissioner Olli Rehn said that an independent Scotland would be unable to meet EU membership requirements if it shared sterling informally, as it would not have an independent central bank.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond disputed this, restating his belief that a sterling currency union would be formed and pledging to create the necessary financial institutions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Socialist Party favoured an independent Scottish currency, pegged to sterling in the short term.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party said that keeping sterling as 'a short term transitional arrangement' should not be ruled out, but also that the Scottish Government should 'keep an open mind about moving towards an independent currency'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In early 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation described retention of the pound as a good transitional arrangement, but recommended the eventual establishment of an independent Scottish currency to 'insulate' Scotland from the UK's 'economic instability'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Other proponents of an independent Scottish currency included Yes Scotland chairman Dennis Canavan and former SNP deputy leader Jim Sillars.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 9 September 2014, Mark Carney, governor of the Bank of England, said that a currency union between an independent Scotland and the remainder of the UK would be 'incompatible with sovereignty'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He added that cross-border ties on tax, spending and banking rules are a prerequisite: 'You only have to look across the continent to look at what happens if you don't have those components in place ...
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At present under devolution, Scotland controls only 7% of our revenues.' Carney's comments received vocal support from Darling and the GMB trade union.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Barnett formula, introduced in the late 1970s, had resulted in higher per-capita public spending in Scotland than England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] If an allocation of North Sea oil revenue based on geography was included, Scotland also produced more per capita tax revenue than the UK average in the years immediately preceding the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute for Fiscal Studies reported in November 2012 that a geographic share of North Sea oil would more than cover the higher public spending, but warned that oil prices are volatile and that they are drawn from a finite resource.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Government Expenditure and Revenue Scotland report for 2012/13 found that North Sea oil revenue had fallen by 41.5% and that Scotland's public spending deficit had increased from £4.6 billion to £8.6 billion.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2012, the Scottish Government's Finance Secretary John Swinney prepared a confidential cabinet briefing paper on the financial impact of Scottish independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that an independent Scotland would face public spending cuts, lower pensions and welfare spending, and high levels of debt.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that Scotland's public finances would be heavily dependent on volatile and declining oil revenues, and suggested that the affordability of the state pension in an independent Scotland would be at risk.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report further warned that the SNP's plans for an oil fund under independence would "require some downward revision in current spending." Swinney's cabinet paper was kept secret before being leaked to the press in 2013, a year after it was drafted.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Darling, the leader of the Better Together campaign opposed to Scottish independence, described the leaked report as a "hammer blow" to the SNP's economic credibility.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A Scottish Government spokesman insisted that the report's findings had been "overtaken by events".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, the UK government published an analysis identifying a 'Union dividend' of £1,400 per year for each person in Scotland, mainly due to the higher level of public spending.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government disputed this analysis, saying that each Scot would be £1,000 better off per year under independence by 2030.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Three economic experts said that both estimates were possible, but they depended on unknown variables such as the division of UK government debt, future North Sea oil revenues, possible spending commitments of an independent Scotland and future productivity gains.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In its analysis, the UK government also estimated setup costs of £1.5 billion (1% of GDP) for establishing an independent state, or possibly £2.7 billion (180 public bodies costing £15 million each).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Patrick Dunleavy of the London School of Economics criticised the UK government's 'ludicrous' use of his research in arriving at the latter figure.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Treasury said that their main figure (£1.5 billion) was based on estimates by Robert Young of Western University.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two of the main unionist parties in Scotland called on the SNP to publish their own estimate of the setup costs of an independent state, but the Scottish government said that an estimate was not possible as the final bill would depend on negotiations with the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Dunleavy estimated immediate setup costs of £200 million in a report commissioned by *The Sunday Post*, with 'total transition costs' of between £600 million and £1,500 million in the first 10 years of independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit rating that an independent Scotland would merit also became a subject of debate.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit-rating agency Fitch said in 2012 that it could not give an opinion on what rating Scotland would have, because Scottish finances would largely depend on the result of negotiations between the UK and Scotland and specifically the division of UK assets and liabilities.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research published by Moody's in May 2014 said that an independent Scotland would be given an A rating, comparable with Poland, the Czech Republic and Mexico.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] An A rating would have been two grades below its then rating for the UK, which Moody's said would be unaffected by Scottish independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The UK government controlled most energy issues, although control over planning laws had allowed the Scottish government to prevent the construction of new nuclear power stations in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence wanted to retain a single energy market for the whole of Great Britain after independence, to maintain price stability and support for suppliers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that independence would threaten that single energy market.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister, professor of economics at Aberdeen University, said that although independence would affect the relationship, it was likely that there would be continued English demand for electricity generated in Scotland due to the lack of spare capacity elsewhere.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The second largest supplier of energy in the UK, SSE plc, believed that a single market would be the most likely outcome under independence, although it would require negotiations that may have led to changes to the existing system.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Caroline Flint said that independence would mean higher energy bills in Scotland, as its customers would have to pay more to support renewable energy in Scotland, which represented one-third of the UK total.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister said that bills were likely to increase across the whole of Great Britain because renewable schemes and new nuclear power stations in England were receiving higher subsidies than the power plants which were due for closure due to environmental regulations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that there was a distinction between existing and proposed renewable schemes in that the existing schemes had already been paid for, whereas any new construction required the promise of subsidy from the consumer.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Energy and Climate Change Secretary Ed Davey said Scottish generators would no longer be eligible for UK subsidies, which would increase energy bills for consumers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Approximately 90% of the United Kingdom's North Sea oil fields were located in Scottish territorial waters.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The tax revenue generated from an offshore site was not counted within the nation or region nearest to it, but was instead allocated to the UK Continental Shelf.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The revenue from North Sea oil was used to support current expenditure, and the UK did not create a sovereign oil fund (as in Norway).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP believed that a portion of the revenues should have been invested in a sovereign oil fund.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government, citing industry body Oil and Gas UK, estimated in *Scotland's Future* that there were 24 billion barrels of oil equivalent still to be extracted.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Ian Wood, founder of oil services company Wood Group, said in August 2014 that he believed there were between 15 and 16.5 billion boe and that the impact from declining production would be felt by 2030.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2014, an investigation by industry recruitment website *Oil and Gas People* found that there were extensive oil reserves to the west of the Western Isles and Shetland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The report anticipated that the region would be developed within the next 10 years because of improvements in drilling technology, rig design and surveying.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP advocated that an independent Scotland should become a full member state of the European Union (EU) with some exemptions, such as not having to adopt the euro.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was debate over whether Scotland would be required to reapply for membership and whether it could retain the UK's opt-outs.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The European Commission (EC) offered to provide an opinion to an existing member state on the matter, but the UK government confirmed it would not seek this advice, as it did not want to negotiate the terms of independence in advance of the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was no precedent for an EU member state dividing into two sovereign countries after joining the EU.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence stated that an independent Scotland would become an EU member by treaty amendment under Article 48 of the EU treaties.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that this would not be possible and that an independent Scotland would need to apply for EU membership under Article 49, which would require ratification by each member state.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, Christina McKelvie, Convener of the European and External Relations Committee of the Scottish Parliament, asked Viviane Reding, Vice-President of the European Commission, whether Article 48 would apply.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Reding replied that EU treaties would no longer apply to a territory that secedes from a member state.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She also said that Article 49 would be the route to apply to become a member of the EU.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] José Manuel Barroso, president of the European Commission, said earlier that an independent Scotland would have to apply for EU membership, while the rest of the UK would continue to be a member.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2014, he reiterated that for Scotland to join the EU would be 'extremely difficult, if not impossible'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former prime minister Sir John Major suggested in November 2013 that Scotland would need to reapply for EU membership, but that this would mean overcoming opposition to separatism among other member states.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond cited a letter from Mario Tenreiro of the EC's secretariat general that said it would be legally possible to renegotiate the situation of the UK and Scotland within the EU by unanimous agreement of all member states.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Spain's European Affairs minister reiterated their position two days before the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir David Edward, a former European Court judge, said that the EU institutions and member states would be 'obliged' to start negotiations before independence took effect to decide the future relationship.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He said this would be achieved by agreed amendment of the existing Treaties (Article 48), rather than a new Accession Treaty (Article 49).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Graham Avery, the EC's honorary director-general, agreed with Edward.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Avery wrote a report, published by the European Policy Centre, which said that EU leaders would probably allow Scotland to be part of the EU because of the legal and practical difficulties that would arise from excluding it.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a research paper, Professor Sionaidh Douglas-Scott of Oxford University wrote that the EU law normally takes a 'pragmatic and purposive approach' to issues not already provided for by existing treaties.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, the Republic of Ireland's Minister of European Affairs, Lucinda Creighton, said that if Scotland were to become independent, it 'would have to apply for membership and that can be a lengthy process'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She later clarified those remarks, writing that she 'certainly did not at any stage suggest that Scotland could, should or would be thrown out of the EU'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that Barroso's comments on the legal position had 'no basis in the European treaties'.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, David Cameron committed the Conservative Party to a referendum before the end of 2017 on UK membership of the EU if they won the 2015 general election.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Legislation for an in/out EU referendum was approved by the House of Commons in November 2013.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Studies showed some divergence in attitudes to the EU in Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, there was a majority for withdrawal in England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland said that the UK government plans for an EU referendum had caused "economic uncertainty" for Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During a CBI Scotland event attended by Cameron, businessman Michael Rake criticised him for creating uncertainty about EU membership.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In response to such criticism, Cameron pointed to examples of inward investment in the UK that he said was not happening in the rest of Europe.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some commentators suggested that the UK leaving the EU could undermine the case for Scottish independence, since free trade, freedom of movement and the absence of border controls between Scotland and England could no longer be assumed.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Responsibility for most aspects of health care was devolved to the Scottish Parliament when it was established in 1999.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government enacted health policies which were different from those in England, such as abolishing charges for prescriptions and elderly personal care.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] NHS Scotland was operationally independent of the NHS in the rest of the United Kingdom since the formation of the NHS in 1948.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence argued that independence was needed because possible reductions in the NHS budget in England would result in reduced funding for Scotland, which would make it difficult to maintain the existing service.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Harry Burns, a former chief medical officer for Scotland, said in July 2014 that he thought independence could be beneficial for public health because it may give people greater control of their lives.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, about 100 medical workers, including surgeons, consultant doctors, GPs, pharmacists, dentists, hospital porters and janitors joined a pro-independence campaign group called "NHS for Yes".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, opponents argued that a subsequent drop in funding to an independent Scottish Government would have a significantly larger effect upon the budget.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Concerns were also raised about the impact on the medical research sector in Scotland from the loss of UK wide research funding.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two days before the referendum, papers indicating "a funding gap of £400–£450m in the next two financial years, 2015–17", for Scotland's NHS, resulting from Scottish government policies, were leaked to the media.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A Scottish government spokesperson commented that the papers were from "part of the regular discussions among NHS leaders to plan for NHS Scotland's future".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents of independence said that being part of the UK was crucial in allowing Scots to obtain specialist treatment elsewhere in the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Although operationally independent, NHS Scotland had reciprocal arrangements in place with the NHS services in the rest of the UK and specialist services were shared.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders, a unionist campaign group, ran a cinema advert which claimed that Scots would find it more difficult to obtain treatment at the Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH), a London facility which provided specialist care for children.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders withdrew the advert after GOSH complained that it had not been consulted about the advert and stated that they had reciprocal health care agreements with numerous countries.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The white paper on independence proposed that an independent Scotland would open around 100 embassies around the world.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Prime Minister David Cameron suggested that an independent Scotland would be "marginalised" at the United Nations, where the UK is a permanent member of the Security Council.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Prime Minister John Major suggested that the UK could lose its permanent seat at the Security Council if Scotland became independent.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Forming a republic was favoured by some pro-independence political parties and organisations, including the Scottish Green Party and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP favoured an independent Scotland continuing to recognise Elizabeth II as Queen of Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Christine Grahame MSP said she believed that party policy was to hold a referendum on the matter, due to a 1997 SNP conference resolution.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some media reports suggested that the announcement on 8 September of the pregnancy of the Duchess of Cambridge with her second child would help pro-union sentiment.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Queen's official position on Scottish independence was neutral.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Just prior to the referendum, Elizabeth II said in a private conversation that she hoped people would "think very carefully about the future".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK State Pensions were managed by the UK government, paying £113.10 per week to a single person who is of state pension age in the 2013/14 tax year.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The state pension age for men was 65, but this was due to rise to 66 in 2020 and 67 by 2028.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research found that an independent Scotland could delay these increases, due to a lower life expectancy.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Scotland's Future* white paper pledged to maintain a state pension at a similar rate to the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former UK Prime Minister Gordon Brown said in April 2014 that Scotland had an above-average share of the public-sector pension bill and concluded that pensions would be protected by sharing risks and resources within the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK government pensions minister Steve Webb said in May 2014 that Scots would be entitled to the current levels of state pension after independence because they had accumulated rights within the existing system.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Webb went on to say that there would need to be negotiations between the UK and Scotland as to how these pensions would be paid.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In relation to private pension schemes, a report by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland expressed concern that there were no plans to deal with EU regulations that may affect the funding of cross-border defined benefit schemes.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The EC decided in March 2014 not to relax these regulations, which require cross-border schemes to be fully funded.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scotland hosted the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, less than two months before the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish team won a record number of gold medals, which the writer Alan Bisset said would help give voters more belief and confidence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *Sunday Herald* columnist Ian Bell took an opposing view, saying that sporting success would be unlikely to aid support for independence, due to the lengthy and passionate debate on the subject.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Labour first minister Henry McLeish published a report in May 2014 that found no obvious barriers to an independent Scotland competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] McLeish said that some athletes, particularly those in team sports, may choose to compete for the existing Great Britain team rather than Scotland, as they would be nationals of both states.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Gordon Brown pointed to the 2012 medal count for Great Britain, saying that it showed the success of the union.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish athletes were involved in 13 of the 65 medals won by Great Britain in 2012, but only three of those were won without assistance by athletes from other parts of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Chris Hoy said in May 2013 that it would "take time" for Scottish athletes to "establish themselves in a new training environment", and indicated that the good performance of Scottish athletes in the Great Britain team would not automatically translate into that of an independent Scotland team.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Hoy also said that he believed the lack of facilities and coaching infrastructure in Scotland would have to be addressed by an independent state.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The prospect of an independent Scotland raised questions about the future of the Northern Isles (Orkney and Shetland) and the Western Isles, island groups off the Scottish mainland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some islanders called for separate referendums to be held in the islands on 25 September 2014, one week after the Scottish referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, the Scottish Parliament published an online petition it had received calling for such referendums, which was supported by Shetland MSP Tavish Scott.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The proposed referendums would have asked islanders to choose from three options: that the island group should become an independent country; that it should remain in Scotland; or that (in the event of Scottish independence) it should remain in the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The third option would have implemented a conditional promise made in 2012 by an SNP spokesperson, who said that Orkney and Shetland could remain in the United Kingdom if their "drive for self-determination" was strong enough.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Politicians in the three island groups referred to the Scottish referendum as the most important event in their political history "since the inception of the island councils in 1975".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Angus Campbell, leader of the Western Isles, said that the ongoing constitutional debate offered the "opportunity for the three island councils to secure increased powers for our communities to take decisions which will benefit the economies and the lives of those who live in the islands".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a meeting of the island councils in March 2013, leaders of the three territories discussed their future in the event of Scottish independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] This included whether the islands could demand and achieve autonomous status within either Scotland or the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Among the scenarios proposed were achieving either Crown Dependency status or self-government modelled after the Faroe Islands, in association with either Scotland or the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle, Orkney's council leader, described pursuing Crown Dependency status as the least likely option, as it would threaten funding from the EU, which was essential for local farmers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alasdair Allan, MSP for the Western Isles, said independence could have a positive impact on the isles, as "crofters and farmers could expect a substantial uplift in agricultural and rural development funding via the Common Agricultural Policy if Scotland were an independent member state of the EU".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In July 2013, the Scottish government made the Lerwick Declaration, indicating an interest in devolving power to Scotland's islands.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By November, it had committed to devolving further powers to Orkney, Shetland and the Western Isles in the event of independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle called for legislation to that effect to be introduced regardless of the referendum result.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He stated that he did not want such circumstances to arise, "and the best way to avoid this was to vote no in the referendum".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2012–13, Scottish universities received 13.1% of Research Councils UK funding.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alan Trench of University College London said that Scottish universities had received a "hugely disproportionate" level of funding and would no longer be able to access it following independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, suggested that independence would mean Scottish universities losing £210m in research funding.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Institute of Physics in Scotland warned that access to international facilities such as the CERN Large Hadron Collider, the European Space Agency, and European Southern Observatory could require renegotiation by the Scottish government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It also expressed concerns about research funding from UK charities and the reaction of international companies with Scottish facilities.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government's education secretary, Michael Russell, said that Scotland's universities had a "global reputation" that would continue to attract investment after independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the principal of the University of Aberdeen said that Scottish universities could continue to access UK research funding through a "single research area" that crossed both nations' boundaries.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Bell, professor of economics at the University of Stirling, said that cross-border collaboration might continue, but Scottish universities could still lose their financial advantage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Roger Cook of the Scotland Institute pointed out that although Scottish universities had received a higher share of Research Councils funding, they were much less dependent on this as a source of funding than their counterparts in England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professors from Scotland's five medical schools wrote an open letter warning that independence would mean Scotland's researcher base being "denied its present ability to win proportionately more grant funding".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Questions were asked whether Scotland, as an economy of a smaller size than the UK, would still support the same level of research activity, and what additional efforts might be required to establish a system of research councils "north of the border".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Jo Shaw, Salvesen chair of European institutions at the University of Edinburgh, noted that in smaller states, relationships between universities and research funders became "cosy", and led to a "corporatist" approach.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the time of the referendum, Students domiciled in Scotland did not pay tuition fees.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Students domiciled in the rest of the UK were charged fees of up to £9,000 per annum by Scottish universities, but those from other EU member states were not charged fees due to EU law.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] If Scotland had become an independent state, students from the rest of the UK would have been in the same position as students from the rest of the EU.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A University of Edinburgh study found that this would cause a loss in funding, which could have squeezed out Scottish students.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It concluded that the EU may allow a quota system for some specialist subjects, such as medicine, where there was a clear need for local students to be trained for particular careers, but that other subjects would not be eligible.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The study also found that their third suggestion would run against the spirit of the Bologna agreement, which aimed to encourage EU student mobility.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government stated in its white paper, *Scotland's Future*, that the present tuition fees arrangement would remain in place in an independent Scotland, as the EU allowed for different fee arrangements in "exceptional circumstances".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Ján Figeľ, a former EU commissioner for education, said in January 2014 that it would be illegal for an independent Scotland to apply a different treatment to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A report by a House of Commons select committee stated that it would cost an independent Scottish government £150 million to provide free tuition to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A group of academics campaigning for independence expressed concern that the present arrangements would not continue if Scotland stayed within the UK, due to public spending cuts in England and the consequential effects of the Barnett formula.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign argued that control of welfare policy would be a major benefit of independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to the Institute for Fiscal Studies, independence would "give the opportunity for more radical reform, so that the [welfare] system better reflects the views of the Scottish people".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland and deputy first minister Nicola Sturgeon said the existing welfare system could only be guaranteed by voting for independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (SCVO), which represents charities, called for a separate welfare system to be established in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In November 2013, the Scottish government pledged to use the powers of independence to reverse key aspects of the Welfare Reform Act 2012, which was implemented across the UK despite opposition from a majority of Scotland's MPs.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It said it would abolish Universal Credit and the bedroom tax.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP also criticised Rachel Reeves, Labour's shadow secretary of state for work and pensions, for saying that a future UK Labour government would be even tougher on benefits than the Cameron–Clegg coalition government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour politician Jim Murphy, a former Secretary of State for Scotland, said that he was "fiercely committed" to devolving welfare powers to the Scottish Parliament, but also warned that independence would be disruptive and would not be beneficial.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish Labour's Devolution Commission recommended in March 2014 that some aspects of the welfare state, including housing benefit and attendance allowance, should be devolved.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Feminist economist Ailsa McKay, a supporter of the Radical Independence movement, argued that an independent Scotland should change its welfare system dramatically by offering all its people a basic income.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A number of demonstrations in support of independence were co-ordinated following the announcement of the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally for Scottish Independence in September 2012 drew a crowd of between 5,000 and 10,000 people to Princes Street Gardens.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The event was repeated in September 2013; police estimated that over 8,000 people took part in the march, while organisers and the Scottish Police Federation claimed between 20,000 and 30,000 people took part in the combined march and rally.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally was criticised in both 2012 and 2013 for the involvement of groups like the Scottish Republican Socialist Movement and Vlaamse Volksbeweging.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Five days before the referendum vote, the Orange Order – a Protestant brotherhood – held a major anti-independence march and rally in Edinburgh.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It involved at least 15,000 Orangemen, loyalist bands and supporters from Scotland and across the UK, and was described as the biggest pro-Union demonstration of the campaign up to that date.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A rally for UK unity, organised by the Let's Stay Together campaign, was attended by 5,000 people in London's Trafalgar Square on the Monday preceding the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Similar events were held in London, Bristol, Leeds, Cardiff, Manchester and Belfast on the day before the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Jim Murphy conducted a Scotland-wide tour to campaign for the No side, intending to visit 100 towns and cities in 100 days before the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 28 August he suspended his tour, after being hit by an egg in Kirkcaldy, and it was resumed on 3 September.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Murphy said that he had been subjected to "co-ordinated abuse" from Yes supporters and pointed to evidence of this on social media.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together released footage of events in the tour where he was heckled by members of the public, some of whom called him a "traitor", "parasite", "terrorist" and "quisling".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Cameron said that "there's nothing wrong with a bit of heckling, but throwing things isn't necessarily part of the democratic process".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Salmond pointed out that people had "every entitlement to peaceful protest", but also said that "people shouldn't throw eggs at somebody full stop".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the launch of the Yes Scotland campaign in May 2012, Alex Salmond said that the case for independence would be driven by community activism and "online wizardry".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The not-for-profit and non-partisan *What Scotland Thinks* project tracked poll and survey data, including online activity, during the referendum campaign.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Using data from the Applied Quantitative Methods Network (AQMeN) research centre, the project compiled the social media activity of the two main campaigns, Yes Scotland and Better Together, by monitoring their respective Facebook and Twitter accounts since August 2013.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *What Scotland Thinks* published a report in February 2014 stating that the Yes Scotland campaign was gaining more Facebook likes.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Following the launch of the White Paper on 26 November, the average gap between the two Facebook pages grew from about 8,000 to about 23,000 by February 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Analysis of the campaigns' Twitter accounts showed the gap between the campaigns increased from approximately 8,000 followers in August 2013 to 13,804 followers in February 2014, in favour of Yes Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The project published a further report in June 2014 saying that greater online activity for Yes Scotland had continued.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor Michael Keating said in April 2014 that the pro-independence movement was visibly stronger and fighting a "ground war", while unionist supporters were fighting an "'air war' of facts and figures".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The launch of online celebrity videos from both viewpoints was reported by the media in mid-July 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The "Let's Stay Together" campaign group produced a YouTube video called "'Scotland, you're my best friend'", featuring John Barrowman, Ross Kemp and Eddie Izzard.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A pro-independence video was produced by Yes Scotland and appeared on the campaign's YouTube channel.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Titled "✘ on September 18th #voteYes", the video features 32 people, including David Hayman, Martin Compston and Stuart Braithwaite.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The pro-independence organisation National Collective was identified by the *Independent* newspaper as the initiators of an online hashtag campaign that began in mid-August 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing for the *Independent*, Antonia Molloy said that the previous "#IndyReasons" hashtag campaign served as the inspiration for the "#YesBecause" campaign that was observed on the Twitter, Facebook and Vine social media platforms.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] From 21 August, users were invited to explain their reasons for voting "Yes" and #YesBecause was trending on Twitter after an hour from the launch.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) reported on 22 August that a "#NoBecause" campaign emerged in opposition to the Collective.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Debates over the issue of independence took place on television, in communities, and within universities and societies since the announcement of the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The STV current affairs programme *Scotland Tonight* televised a series of debates: Nicola Sturgeon v Michael Moore, Sturgeon v Anas Sarwar, Sturgeon v Alistair Carmichael and Sturgeon v Johann Lamont.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 21 January 2014, BBC Two Scotland broadcast the first in a series of round-table debates, which was filmed in Greenock and chaired by James Cook.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign repeatedly called for a televised debate between UK Prime Minister David Cameron and First Minister of Scotland Alex Salmond.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] These calls for a one-on-one debate were dismissed by Cameron on the basis that the referendum is "for Scots to decide" and the debate should be "between people in Scotland who want to stay, and people in Scotland who want to go".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Calls for such a debate were also supported by former Prime Minister Gordon Brown who said it would be a "good idea".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together chairman Alistair Darling accused Salmond of "running scared" from debating him instead, although Sturgeon stated in 2013 that a Salmond–Darling debate would take place at some point.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Darling refused a public debate with Yes Scotland chairman Blair Jenkins.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UKIP leader Nigel Farage also challenged Salmond to debate, but Farage was dismissed by an SNP spokeswoman as "an irrelevance in Scotland".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After weeks of negotiation, a debate between Salmond and Darling was arranged.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The programme, titled as *Salmond & Darling: The Debate*, was broadcast by STV on 5 August 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The debate, moderated by Bernard Ponsonby, saw both politicians make opening statements and cross-examine each other before taking questions from the audience.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the end of the clash, they were both given the chance to make a closing speech.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Both campaign groups claimed victory in the debate.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A snap poll conducted by ICM stated Darling won the debate by 56% to 44%.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In his analysis of the ICM poll, Professor John Curtice detected little movement either way as a result of the debate.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A second debate between Salmond and Darling, titled *Scotland Decides: Salmond versus Darling* was shown on BBC One Scotland (and BBC Two in the rest of the UK) on 25 August, and was hosted by Glenn Campbell.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond was perceived to have won the debate, and a snap poll conducted by ICM Research stated Salmond won the debate by 71% to 29%.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, BBC Scotland chiefs appeared before a Scottish Parliament committee to face questions from MSPs about the broadcaster's coverage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During that session, BBC Scotland director Ken MacQuarrie disputed the findings of Robertson's study, saying that its conclusions were largely based upon "flawed analysis" and had contained factual errors.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During the latter stages of the campaign there were further allegations by some independence supporters that the BBC – the UK's national broadcaster – was biased against Scottish independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In an interview for the *Sunday Herald*, Alex Salmond said he believed the BBC had been unconsciously biased against independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former BBC journalist Paul Mason commented: "Not since Iraq have I seen BBC News working at propaganda strength like this".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The BBC replied that "Our coverage of the referendum story is fair and impartial in line with the editorial guidelines".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Massie wrote in *The Spectator* that the BBC's coverage was consistent with their attitude towards other government proposals of such magnitude and that it was incumbent upon the Yes campaign to prove its assertions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 29 June, several hundred independence supporters gathered in a demonstration outside BBC Pacific Quay, the main BBC studio in Glasgow, in protest at its alleged bias.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A week before the vote, BBC political editor Nick Robinson said in a news item that Salmond "didn't answer" his questions at a press conference.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Several thousand independence supporters then protested at the BBC Scotland headquarters, accusing the BBC of broadcasting pro-Union "propaganda" and "lies".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *The Independent* reported that the protesters accused Robinson of working "with the Treasury to spread lies about the dangers to business and financial services of an independent Scotland".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alastair Campbell said that the "organised protests" amounted to media censorship "not far off" Vladimir Putin's Russia, telling Twitter users they should "Vote YES for intimidation".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The National Union of Journalists (NUJ) asked people to think about the implications of alleging journalistic bias when its members were only asking difficult questions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Robinson later expressed his "regret" at using the phrase "didn't answer" in his report and criticised the protests.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Speaking after the referendum, Yes Scotland chief executive Blair Jenkins said that he did not believe there was a "systemic bias" against Yes or any "corporate intent to disadvantage the Yes campaign".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In addition to the incidents described above, there were reports of intimidation during the campaign.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A survey of the 133 business leaders who signed a public letter backing the Union reported that half of respondents "said that they had felt intimidated or pressurised by SNP or the Yes campaign as a result of their views".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Daily Telegraph* reported that other businesspeople had been unwilling to express an opinion on the referendum publicly because they were concerned about a loss of business from the SNP-led Scottish government or local government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The NUJ called for abuse and bullying of its members, which had been led by online attacks, to end, commenting that, "For the duration of the referendum there has been hostility to journalists doing their jobs".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Police Federation stated that criminal acts related to the referendum were few in number and criticised those "suggesting a minority of mindless idiots are representative of anything".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor John Curtice stated in January 2012 that polling showed support for independence at 32%–38% of the Scottish population, which represented a slight decline from 2007, when the SNP had first formed the Scottish government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By 2012, there had been no poll evidence of majority support for independence, although the share "vehemently opposed to independence" had declined.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to Curtice, the polls were stable during most of 2013, with "no" leading by an average of 17% with a year to go.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Polling expert Nate Silver said in 2013 that the yes campaign had "virtually no chance" of winning the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After the referendum, Silver said that although his prediction had been proven "right" he had done little research beforehand.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The gap narrowed after the release of the Scottish government white paper on independence: an average of five polls in December 2013 and January 2014 gave 39% yes and 61% no, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The polls tightened further after the Chancellor of the Exchequer, George Osborne, stated in February that the UK government was opposed to a currency union; the average yes support increased to 43%, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was little movement in the following months, with the average continuing to show 43% yes and 57% no (excluding don't knows) in July 2014 and August 2014.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In early September, polls indicated that the vote would be closer than had been indicated earlier.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 6 September a YouGov poll gave those in favour 47% versus 45% for those against; excluding those undecided, the figures were 51% and 49%, respectively.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The final polls, taken in the last few days of the campaign, indicated a lead for No of between 4% and 6%.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Soon after polling stations had closed, YouGov released a final poll that had been taken during the day of voting, indicating 46% Yes, 54% No.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing after the referendum, Nate Silver pointed out that the final margin of victory for No was greater than that indicated by the opinion polls.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He suggested that this could have been due to less enthusiastic voters being more pro-Union, which may not have been reflected in the polls.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Stephen Fisher, a sociology professor at Oxford University, noted in a study of other constitutional referendums that pollsters had tended to overestimate the "Yes" option.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2015, a poll carried out by YouGov found a slight majority of support for independence among people born in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Independence Referendum Bill identified the convener of the Electoral Management Board for Scotland as chief counting officer for the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The chief counting officer, Mary Pitcaithly, was supported by a counting officer in each of the 32 local authority areas of Scotland, who was typically the chief executive for that local authority.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Voting took place between 07:00 and 22:00 BST in "polling places", which included schools, church halls, libraries and community centres.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Those who were still queuing when polls closed were not denied the chance to vote.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Votes from the 32 local government areas were counted and announced by each area separately.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Results came in during the early hours of 19 September, with the first result being from Clackmannanshire, and the last being from Highland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 55.3% voted against independence, with a turnout of 84.6%.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 28 of the 32 council areas voted "No", although the four areas that voted "Yes" (Dundee, Glasgow, North Lanarkshire and West Dunbartonshire) contained over 20% of the Scottish electorate.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The overall turnout of 84.6% was very high for Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Turnout was around 50–60% for elections to the Scottish and UK parliaments in the early 21st century.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The most recent United Kingdom general election with a comparable turnout was in 1950, when 83.9% voted.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The last ballot in the United Kingdom with a higher turnout than 84.6% was in January 1910, when no women and fewer men were allowed to vote (i.e., before universal suffrage applied to UK elections).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Of the 32 areas, East Dunbartonshire had the highest turnout at 91.0%, and Glasgow the lowest at 75.0%.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An academic study, surveying 5,000 Scottish voters soon after the referendum, found that the majority for No was formed by an "unusual alliance" of the very young, average earners, Protestants and women.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The study supported polling evidence that there was a gender gap, but countered beliefs that higher earners had supported No and that younger voters had mostly voted Yes.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to John Curtice, polling evidence indicates that support for independence was highest among those aged in their late 20s and early 30s, with a higher No vote among those aged between 16 and 24.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was an age gap at the referendum, with elderly voters being the most likely to vote against independence and younger voters aged under 55, except for those aged between 16 and 24, generally being more in favour of independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This was picked up by other academics, with data from the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation study from 2012 indicating that the six most deprived local authorities in Scotland returned the highest Yes vote shares at the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This is an incomplete list as not all local authorities counted by ward or constituency.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The constituency results are primarily obtained through local authority breakdowns of the result or the constituency boundaries being co-terminous with the local government district.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day of the referendum, Michael Ashcroft conducted a poll of over 2,000 voters to identify the major reasons for their voting choices.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This poll found that among No voters, more than half (57%) stated the pound sterling was one of the most important factors in their decision.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Among Yes voters, the biggest single motivation was "disaffection with Westminster politics".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron admitted he was "very embarrassed" for revealing the Queen's political view, which she had guarded in her own comments.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Alex Salmond, the Scottish First Minister and leader of the SNP, stated that he accepted the "verdict of the people" and called upon "all Scots to follow suit in accepting the democratic verdict of the people of Scotland".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He called the referendum a "triumph for the democratic process and for participation in politics".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He also resigned as SNP leader and as First Minister, saying that "for me as leader my time is nearly over but for Scotland the campaign continues and the dream shall never die".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Northern Ireland's First Minister Peter Robinson and Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones responded positively to the result.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Robinson was "delighted Scotland has voted to remain in the Union".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was a large international reaction to the results of the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The White House congratulated Scotland on their "full and energetic exercise of democracy".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President Barack Obama noted the "debate, discussion, and passionate yet peaceful deliberations" and welcomed the result, saying he looked forward to "continuing our strong and special relationship with all the people of Great Britain and Northern Ireland".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] John Baird, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Canada, welcomed the decision and praised the conduct of the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Angela Merkel, the Chancellor of Germany, said that, "We [the German government] have always respected the fact that this referendum was called and that the central government in London agreed to this.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] And now we respect the outcome of it as well".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] When asked how she felt about the result she replied "I will not comment on this but just smile".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We look forward to working with all parties across these islands in the years ahead.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Good Friday Agreement of 1998 is the historic template for harmonious and mutually beneficial development of the totality of relationships among the peoples of these islands.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In particular, it has led to a transformation in relationships between the two great traditions on this island".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We have noted that the UK government has extended concrete promises in this regard.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Facing the result of the referendum, Erna Solberg, Prime Minister of Norway, stated to Norwegian broadcaster NRK she was 'glad' Scotland chose to remain in the union and that Scottish independence could have become challenging for Norway as a neighboring country.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Spanish Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, in a video message, said that the Scottish have avoided serious consequences and "have chosen the most favorable option for everyone; for themselves, for all of Britain, and for the rest of Europe".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Iñigo Urkullu, the President of the Basque Country, stated on the day of the referendum that as the British Government had allowed Scotland to freely decide its own future, the responsibility of the Basque government was to "follow Scotland's footsteps" in securing a similar agreement in Spain.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Artur Mas, President of the Generalitat of Catalonia, described the referendum as a model for a future vote in the Catalonia, and said "What happened in Scotland is not a setback for us, because what we really want in Catalonia is to have the chance to vote".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day after the Scottish referendum, the Catalan parliament voted to hold a "popular consultation" on Catalan independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Spanish government said that such a vote would be unconstitutional, but a referendum was held on 9 November 2014 anyway.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The large majority (80%) voted for Catalonia to be an independent country, although two-thirds of Catalans did not participate in the referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Secretary General of NATO Anders Fogh Rasmussen said that he fully-respected "the choice that the people of Scotland have made".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President of the European Commission José Manuel Barroso said the Scottish vote was good for a "united, open, and stronger Europe".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Ten voters discovered that someone had voted under their names at polling stations in Glasgow, a method of fraud termed 'personation', and this led to an investigation by Police Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] During a BBC results broadcast, Scottish Conservative Party leader Ruth Davidson said that "No" campaigners had been "taking tallies" of postal votes and that those showed that the "No" campaign was in the lead.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This resulted in complaints to the electoral commission because the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 stated that people attending proceedings related to the receipt of postal votes must not attempt to ascertain the outcome or "communicate any information" from that voting.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Electoral Commission, who could not investigate criminal allegations, passed the complaints onto Police Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A formal investigation was subsequently opened, which concluded that there was no criminality.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to official Russian observers, the conditions under which the votes were counted were not up to international standards and that the procedure used made it impossible to check on irregularities.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russia's criticism came just months after the international community had rejected the results of a Kremlin-backed referendum held in the Russian-occupied Ukrainian territory of Crimea.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russian officials said that the strong performance of the Scottish National Party (SNP) at the 2015 general election confirmed their suspicions about the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A petition demanding a second referendum, based on allegations of vote-miscounting, gained more than 70,000 signatures within 24 hours.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In response, Chief Counting Officer Mary Pitcaithly declared that the referendum had been "properly conducted".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An official spokesperson reiterated this point, saying that they were "satisfied that all counts throughout Scotland were properly conducted" and that incidents in the footage could be "easily explained" and were being presented as a "'conspiracy' theory".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the night of 19 September, hundreds of unionists arrived to celebrate the 'No'-vote and some attacked independence supporters who had gathered in George Square, Glasgow.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Many of the unionists waved Union Jacks or loyalist flags and chanted "Rule, Britannia!" Police officers were drafted in to separate the groups but some unionists broke through police lines.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A number of people were reportedly beaten and bottles were thrown.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A press-photographer told *The Scotsman* he saw people being "kicked about" and was forced to flee after being threatened.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By the end of the following month, the police had made 32 arrests in relation to the events.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The violence was condemned by politicians from both the 'Yes'- and 'No'-camps.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the weeks following the referendum, thousands of people joined the Scottish National Party, the Scottish Greens, or the Scottish Socialist Party, which had all campaigned for a 'Yes'-vote.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The parties claimed that many of the new members were former Scottish Labour Party members.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By 2 October 2014, SNP membership had tripled from 25,000 to 75,000 people, overtaking the Liberal Democrats as the third-largest political party in the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Conservative MP David Mundell said that 80,000 people had signed up to their "Friends of the Union" group during the campaign.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] These people had not necessarily become full members of the Conservative Party because they were not focussed on increasing the number of "card-carrying" members.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, there were calls for greater unity within Scottish unionism and to vote tactically against nationalist candidates.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A grassroots campaign called "Scotland in Union" aimed to encourage tactical voting at the 2015 general election and to publicise the benefits of Scotland being a part of the United Kingdom.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Analysis by the Electoral Reform Society prior to the 2015 general election identified some constituencies where tactical voting could succeed, but also pointed out that many voters would find it difficult to support another political party.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Writing after the election, Professor John Curtice said that in only one constituency (Edinburgh South) could it be said that tactical voting succeeded in defeating an SNP candidate.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Two days before the referendum, the leaders of the three main UK political parties publicly pledged to devolve "extensive new powers" to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] They also agreed to a timetable proposed by Gordon Brown.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In his speech responding to the referendum results, David Cameron said that an all-party commission, chaired by Lord Smith of Kelvin, would oversee the implementation of the new powers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron also called for an answer to the West Lothian question, by removing the right of Scottish MPs to vote on legislation relating only to England.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This proposal was opposed by Gordon Brown, who signed a petition calling for the additional powers to be devolved without any other conditions being attached.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The proposals were debated at length by the UK and Scottish parliaments.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The bill devolving further powers to Scotland was approved unanimously by the Scottish Parliament in March 2016.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, the SNP took a clear lead over the other parties in Scottish opinion polls.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the 2015 general election, the SNP received 1,454,436 votes, 49.97% of the Scottish vote and 56 out of the 59 Scottish seats contested in the election.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Labour lost forty of their forty-one seats and the Liberal Democrats lost ten of their eleven seats – all to the SNP.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The SNP replaced the Liberal Democrats as the third largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] As the Conservatives won an overall majority in the 2015 UK general election, a UK-wide referendum on European Union membership was held in June 2016.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An overall majority of the UK voted to leave the EU (for "Brexit"), while all of Scotland's council areas voted to remain in the EU.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Shortly afterwards, First Minister Nicola Sturgeon announced her intention to prepare legislation for a second independence referendum.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the June 2017 general election, the first major electoral test after the EU referendum, the SNP won 35 of the 59 Scottish seats in the House of Commons.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This represented a drop of 21 seats from 2015, with the Conservatives, Labour and Liberal Democrats all making gains.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Those results were largely reversed in the December 2019 general election, as the SNP won 48 seats and the Conservatives and Labour both made net losses.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 26 September 2022, a series of underwater explosions and consequent gas leaks occurred on 3 of 4 Nord Stream pipes, rendering them inoperable.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Nord Stream 1 (NS1) and Nord Stream 2 (NS2) are two of twenty-three natural gas pipelines between Europe and Russia.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The leaks were located in international waters, but within the economic zones of Denmark and Sweden.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Both pipelines were built to transport natural gas from Russia to Germany through the Baltic Sea, and are majority owned by the Russian majority state-owned gas company, Gazprom.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Before the leaks, the pipelines were filled with natural gas but were not transporting it as a consequence of the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The leaks occurred one day before Poland and Norway opened the Baltic Pipe running through Denmark, bringing in gas from the North Sea, rather than from Russia as the Nord Stream pipelines do.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Russia asked for an international investigation at the UN Security Council which was rejected with 3 votes in favor out of 15.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Denmark, Germany and Sweden each initiated separate investigations, describing the explosions as sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Swedish and Danish investigations were closed in February 2024 without identifying those responsible, while the German investigation was ongoing.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On August 21, 2025, the Italian police arrested a Ukrainian man on suspicion of being involved in the sabotage, following European arrest warrants issued by German authorities and on September 30 near Warsaw Polish police arrested another Ukrainian, who had evaded arrest since August 2024.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] As of September 2025 the German investigation reportedly had identified seven suspects including former members of a private diving school in Kyiv, one of whom has died.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In October 2025 the suspect arrested in Poland was released when a Polish court denied the German extradition request.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In July 2026, German prosecutors said Ukrainian divers were responsible for the explosions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In 2021, Russia supplied roughly 45% of the natural gas imported by European Union states.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The United States has been a major opponent of the Nord Stream pipelines; former US President Donald Trump said in 2019 that Nord Stream 2 could turn Europe into a "hostage of Russia" and placed sanctions on any company assisting Russia to complete the pipeline.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In December 2020, then President-elect Joe Biden came out forcefully against the opening of the new pipeline and the impact this would have on potential Russian influence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In 2021, the Biden administration lifted the sanctions, stating that while it was "unwavering" in opposition to Nord Stream 2, removing the sanctions was a matter of national interest, to maintain positive relations with Germany and other US allies in Europe.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The second pipeline was completed in September 2021.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Before being sabotaged neither of the Nord Stream pipelines were delivering gas.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] From 31 August 2022, Gazprom had halted delivery via Nord Stream 1 indefinitely, officially because of maintenance.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Both Nord Stream 1 and 2 were however pressurized with gas.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Nord Stream 2 pipeline contained the equivalent of an estimated 150 million cubic metres (5.3 billion cubic feet) to 300 million cubic metres (11 billion cubic feet) of gas, pressurized to over 100 bar, at the time of the explosions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] An environmental impact assessment of NS2 was made in 2019.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] By 2012, corrosion leaks had only occurred in two large pipelines worldwide.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Leaks due to military-type acts and mishaps were considered "very unlikely".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The largest leak in the analysis was defined as a "full-bore rupture (>80 mm [3.1 in])", for example from a sinking ship hitting the pipeline.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Such an unlikely large leak from 54 metres (177 ft) water depth could result in a gas plume up to 15 metres (49 ft) wide at the surface.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] To weigh down the pipe (to ensure negative buoyancy), a 60–110-millimetre (2.4–4.3 in) layer of concrete surrounds the steel.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Each line of the pipeline was made of about 100,000 concrete-weight coated steel pipes each weighing 24 tonnes (53,000 lb) welded together and laid on the seabed.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] To facilitate pigging, the pipelines have a constant internal diameter of 1,153 millimetres (45.4 in), according to Nord Stream.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Sections lie at a depth of around 80–110 metres (260–360 ft).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Geological Survey of Denmark said that a seismometer on Bornholm showed two spikes on 26 September: the first P wave at 02:03 local time (CEST) indicated a magnitude of 2.3 and the second at 19:03 a magnitude of 2.1.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Similar data were provided by a seismometer at Stevns, and by several seismometers in Germany, Sweden (as far away as the station in Kalix 1,300 kilometres or 810 miles north), Finland and Norway.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The seismic data were characteristic of underwater explosions, not natural events, and showed that they happened near the locations where the leaks were later discovered.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Around the same time, pressure in the non-operating pipeline dropped from 10.50 to 0.70 megapascals (105 to 7 bar), as recorded by Nord Stream in Germany.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] After Germany's initial report of pressure loss in Nord Stream 2, a gas leak from the pipeline was discovered by a Danish F-16 interceptor response unit 25 kilometres (16 mi) southeast of Dueodde, Bornholm.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Nord Stream 2 consists of two parallel lines and the leak happened in line A inside the Danish economic zone.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Citing danger to shipping, Danish Maritime Authority closed the sea for all vessels in a 5-nautical-mile (9.3 km; 5.8 mi) zone around the leak site, and advised planes to stay at least 1,000 m (3,300 ft) above it.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Hours after the German office of Nord Stream had reported pressure loss in Nord Stream 1, two gas leaks were discovered on that pipeline by Swedish authorities.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Both parallel lines of Nord Stream 1 were ruptured and the sites of its two leaks were about 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) from each other, with one in the Swedish economic zone and the other in the Danish economic zone.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 28 September, the Swedish Coast Guard clarified that the initially reported leak in the Swedish economic zone actually was two leaks located near each other, bringing the total number of leaks on the Nord Stream pipes to four (two in the Swedish economic zone, two in the Danish).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Danish Defence posted a video of the gas leak on their website which showed that, as of 27 September, the largest of the leaks created turbulence on the water surface of approximately 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) in diameter.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The smallest leak made a circle of about 200 metres (660 ft) in diameter.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Analysts noted the much larger plumes as an indication that the rupture is very large, compared to a presumed technical leak plume of 15 metres (49 ft).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The SwePol power cable between Sweden and Poland passes near two of the leak sites, and was investigated for damage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Tests by Svenska Kraftnät, published on 4 October, indicated the cable was not damaged.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Swedish Navy confirmed that its ships had patrolled the area in the days before the explosions, but would not comment on why it had done so.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] An analysis of AIS-data from MarineTraffic by Swedish media Dagens Nyheter showed Swedish navy vessels in the areas on 21 and 22 September 2022, from five to four days before the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] During the night of the explosions the analysis showed no Swedish vessels in the area.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 1 October, the Danish Energy Agency reported that one of the two pipelines, Nord Stream 2, appeared to have stopped leaking gas as the pressure inside the pipe had stabilized.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The following day, the same agency reported that the pressure had stabilized in both Nord Stream 1 pipelines as well, indicating that the leakage had stopped.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In contrast, Swedish authorities reported on 2 October that gas continued to escape from the two leaks in their economic zone, albeit to a lesser extent than a few days before.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The three leaks that appeared at roughly the same time were relatively close to each other with their gas plumes confined by a 7-nautical-mile-wide (13 km; 8.1 mi) exclusion zone straddling the boundary between the economic zones (EEZ) of Denmark and Sweden.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The distance between the southern- and northernmost leaks is 79 kilometres (49 mi).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The table's timestamps and Richter scale magnitudes are from seismic data characteristic of underwater explosions and matching the locations of the leaks.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Geological Survey of Denmark said that the tremors that had been detected were unlike those recorded during earthquakes, but similar to those recorded during explosions each with a magnitude corresponding to a "larger WW2 bomb".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Swedish public service broadcaster SVT reported that measuring stations in both Sweden and Denmark recorded strong underwater explosions near the Nord Stream pipelines.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The day after the attack Björn Lund, Associate Professor in Seismology at The Swedish National Seismic Network said "there is no doubt that these were explosions".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The German newspaper *Der Tagesspiegel* wrote that the leaks were being investigated for whether they may have been caused by targeted attacks by submarine or clearance divers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 30 September 2022, Denmark and Sweden jointly submitted a letter to the United Nations Security Council stating that the leaks were caused by at least two detonations with "several hundred kilos" of explosives.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to German Federal Government circles, photos taken by the Federal Police with the support of the navy show a leak 8 metres (26 ft) long, which could only be the result of explosives.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In the Swedish exclusive economic zone two technogenic (artificial) craters with a depth of 3 to 5 metres (9.8 to 16.4 ft) were found on the seabed at a distance of about 248 metres (814 ft) from each other, with pipeline debris located up to 250 metres (820 ft) away from the explosion sites.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 18 November 2022, Swedish authorities announced that remains of explosives were found at the site of the leaks, and confirmed that the incident was the result of sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 23 February 2023 explosives expert David Domjahn from the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology stated that the four Richter scale tremors would each have to have been caused by 300–400-kilogram (660–880 lb) C-4 explosive and ruled out the use of shaped charges.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 21 June 2023, underwater drone footage obtained in a collaboration between German RTL, French Libération, Danish Ekstra Bladet and TV 2 from the southernmost sabotage site was published along with an analysis.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The ruptured NS2 pipeline was filmed at a depth of 75 metres (246 ft).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The steel part of the pipe had been severed with a cut that was clean except for a small indentation with the two separated pipe ends being 5 metres (16 ft) apart in a large crater.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] A named demolitions expert formerly with Denmark's Engineer Regiment and with the Danish Defence Intelligence Service argued that the steel was cut with a shaped charge using just a few kilograms of high detonation velocity explosives.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] His opinion was shared by an unnamed French demolitions expert still in active duty.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Two Danish engineers with expertise in pipeline construction argued that the highly pressurised gas released by the explosion could have bent the severed pipeline ends, formed the crater in the seabed, and caused the seismic tremor.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 2 October 2022, Nancy Faeser, German Minister of the Interior and Community, announced that Germany, Denmark and Sweden intend to form a joint investigation team to investigate these seeming acts of sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Also on 14 October, the Swedish prosecutor announced that Sweden would not set up a joint investigation team with Denmark and Germany because that would transfer information related to Swedish national security.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] German public broadcaster ARD also reported that Denmark had rejected a joint investigation team.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Out of the three separate investigations carried out by Germany, Sweden and Denmark, the latter two were closed without publicly assigned responsibility for the damage in February 2024.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The day after the leaks occurred, the Swedish Police Authority opened an investigation of the incident, calling it "major sabotage".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The investigation is conducted in cooperation with other relevant authorities as well as the Swedish Security Service.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] A similar investigation was opened in Denmark.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The two nations were in close contact, and had also been in contact with other countries in the Baltic region and NATO.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Because it happened within international waters (not part of any nation's territorial sea, although within the Danish and Swedish economic zones), neither the Danish Prime Minister nor the Swedish Prime Minister regarded it as an attack on their nation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 3 October 2022 a *Foreign Policy* columnist reported that Russia was dispatching naval vessels to join Swedish and Danish maritime experts at the leak sites.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] *Foreign Policy* reasoned that since the pipelines are Russian-state owned and since the sabotage is not considered a military attack, investigations may be complicated by Russian involvement.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Moscow demanded to be part of the investigations conducted by Denmark and Sweden, but both countries refused, telling Russia to conduct its own investigations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 6 October, the Swedish Security Service said its preliminary investigations in the Swedish exclusive economic zone showed extensive damage and they "found evidence of detonations", strengthening "the suspicions of serious sabotage".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 18 October, the Swedish newspaper *Expressen* released photos it had commissioned of the Nord Stream 1 damage, showing at least 50 metres (160 ft) of pipe missing from its trench, as well as steel debris around the site.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 18 November, the Swedish Security Service concluded that the incident was an act of "gross sabotage", stating that traces of explosives were found on the pipes.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 4 April 2023 a press release from the Swedish prosecutor stated that the "incident had apparently become a game plan for attempts at manipulation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] This speculation is nothing that will affect the investigation which is based on the facts and the information from analyses, crime scene investigations and collaboration with authorities in Sweden and other countries".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 27 April 2023, the Danish Defence Command confirmed that six Russian navy ships including the SS-750 salvage ship able to launch a mini-submarine were operating in the area four days before the explosion.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 14 June 2023, the senior prosecutor for the Swedish Security Service said that there is a strengthened suspicion that a state is behind the sabotage and that he believes it will be possible to determine who is responsible.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Both Sweden and Denmark closed their investigations into the incident in February 2024 without assigning responsibility.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Swedish authorities cited the lack of jurisdiction while the Danish ones said that there was no basis for pursuing a criminal case.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 10 October, the German Public Prosecutor General launched an investigation into suspected intentional causing of an explosion and anti-constitutional sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The procedure is directed against unknown persons.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to the federal authority, it is responsible because it was a serious violent attack on national energy supply, likely to impair Germany's external and internal security.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Federal Criminal Police Office and the Federal Police were commissioned to investigate.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Federal Police had already started an investigative mission with assistance from the German Navy.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Investigators took photos with a Navy underwater drone that showed a leak 8 metres (26 ft) long.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] This, it was said in government circles, could only have been caused by explosives.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 15 October, the left-wing German party Die Linke made a parliamentary inquiry to the government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The German government claimed that no on-site investigation had taken place yet, and refused to disclose information about the presence of NATO or Russian ships near Bornholm on the day of the presumed sabotage, citing state secret.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 2 June 2023, German police conducted a search of a flat near the Polish border and interviewed a woman whose 26-year-old male partner, a Ukrainian national who has returned to Ukraine, was named as a suspect in the investigation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] A 50-foot sailing yacht named *Andromeda*, operated by the suspect, was reportedly near the site of two of the three explosions in the days before they occurred.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] DNA samples were taken, and traces of military explosives were found on *Andromeda*.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The explosive residue on *Andromeda* matched residue found on the pipeline.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 17 July 2024, the German government refused to publish preliminary results of the investigation after the Alternative für Deutschland (AFD) party asked for it.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In August 2024 media reported that in June German authorities issued a European arrest warrant for a Ukrainian national Volodymyr Z. living near Warsaw suspected of having used the yacht *Andromeda* together with two others to sabotage the Nord Stream pipeline.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In August 2025, a 49-year-old Ukrainian man was arrested by carabinieri in San Clemente, Italy, on suspicion of leading the sabotage of the Nord Stream pipelines.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The international arrest warrant issued by German investigators charged him with anti-constitutional sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Some sources identified the suspect as a former officer of the Armed Forces of Ukraine.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to the arrest warrant, the team led by the man comprised a skipper, four divers and an explosives expert, and detonated at least four explosive charges consisting of a mixture of hexogen (RDX) and octogen (HMX) with a weight of 14 to 27 kilograms each in a depth of 70 to 80 meters.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 22 August, he refused a request for extradition by German authorities.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 16 September, a court in Bologna approved the suspect's extradition to Germany.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 15 October, the Supreme Court of Cassation in Rome blocked his extradition to Germany.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 19 November, Italy's highest court approved the extradition.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 23 January 2026 Germany's Federal Court of Justice rejected his claim of immunity.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Oberlandesgericht Hamburg indicted him, changing the charge from unconstitutional sabotage to war crime.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] As of September 2025 seven suspects including former members of a private diving school in Kyiv, have been identified, one of whom has died.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] They allegedly sailed the Andromeda a yacht they had rented with forged identity documents from Rostock to near Bornholm.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 17 October 2025 a Polish court released Volodymyr Z. denying an extradition request from Germany, that had issued a European arrest warrant in August 2024 against Volodymyr Z.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to Polish *Rzeczpospolita* the arrest warrant from Germany was received by Poland's National Public Prosecutor's Office on 21 June 2024 and on 24 June it was received by the District Prosecutor's Office in Warsaw.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Nevertheless, on 6 July the suspect crossed the border into Ukraine.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] German media Der Spiegel cited unnamed sources "in security circles" for a claim that the suspect left Poland in a vehicle with diplomatic plates, used by the Ukrainian embassy in Warsaw.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The National Public Prosecutor's Office has stated that the German authorities created the arrest warrant without entering the suspect's information in the Schengen Information System (SIS II), allowing the suspect to cross the border without being arrested.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* subsequently reported both that the German authorities denied making the procedural error and that the Polish Internal Security Agency was tasked with handling the arrest but did not execute the warrant.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] A spokesperson from the Warsaw District Prosecutor's Office explained that no detention actions were taken and that instead secret, operational actions including surveillance of the suspect's home address were taken.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In September 2025 Polish Rzeczpospolita claimed that Minister of Foreign Affairs and Deputy Prime Minister Radosław Sikorski in private conversations had offered to give the Ukrainian arrested on suspicion of participating in the sabotage both asylum and an order.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Siemoniak further explained that the extradition ruling must be made by a court within 100 days.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 17 October 2025 the Warsaw District Court denied the extradition request and released Volodymyr Z.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The ruling judge elaborated that the court had no evidence in the matter since "only very general information" had been provided from Germany, that the court had not attempted to determine any question of guilt but only that the arrest was not justified.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The judge justified the ruling with the attack being 'military action in a “just war”' and also questioned the German jurisdiction in the matter, arguing that the pipelines were sabotaged in international waters and have majority Russian ownership.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 6 June 2023, *The Washington Post* reported that an intelligence agency of an unnamed European "close ally" had notified the CIA of a Ukrainian military plan for a covert attack on the pipeline.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The plan was to be carried out by a team of divers reporting to Gen.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Valery Zaluzhny, commander-in-chief of the Ukrainian armed forces, but the *Post* did not report any evidence that it had been put into action.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The US reportedly learned of the plan three months before the destruction of the pipeline, and shared the intelligence with Germany and other allies.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Communications from the unnamed European ally were included in the Discord document leak allegedly perpetrated by USAF Airman Jack Teixeira.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] A day after the *Post*'s report, the Ukrainian president rejected allegations that Ukraine had destroyed the pipeline.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Zaluzhny later denied to the *Washington Post* any involvement in the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 13 June 2023, Dutch public broadcaster NOS reported that MIVD, Dutch military intelligence, was the agency that had originally alerted the CIA to the alleged Ukrainian plan.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 17 February 2023, Russia formally submitted a proposal to the Security Council of the United Nations calling for an investigation into the Nord Stream sabotage, and reiterated its request on 20 February 2023.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 24 March 2023, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov stated that Denmark had invited the Russian-controlled operator of the Nord Stream 2 pipeline to help salvage an unidentified object found close to the pipelines, according to the source.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] This new development had been interpreted as a positive sign by Russia as it demands transparency during the investigation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] At the centre of interest is a tubular object protruding from the seabed in the vicinity of the pipeline.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Nord Stream is attempting to salvage this object for further investigation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The blasts are still unexplained but Russia blames the UK and the US for the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 27 March 2023, a UN Security Council motion by Russia for an independent international inquiry into the sabotage failed, with only China and Brazil supporting the motion, while the remaining 12 council members abstained.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] CNN reported that European security officials observed Russian Navy support ships nearby where the leaks later occurred on 26 and 27 September.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] One week prior, Russian submarines were also observed nearby.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Finland's national public broadcasting company Yle compared the incident to the two explosions on a gas pipeline in North Ossetia in January 2006, which were caused by remote-controlled military-grade charges.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The explosions halted Russian gas supply to Georgia after the country had started seeking NATO membership.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In December 2022, *The Washington Post* reported that after months of investigation, there was so far no conclusive evidence that Russia was behind the attack, and numerous European and US officials privately said that Russia may not be to blame after all.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Others who still considered Russia a prime suspect said positively attributing the attack — to any country — may be impossible.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 25 March 2023 T-Online reported on Russian naval activity near the Nord Steam pipelines just a few days before the explosions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 19 September the Russian Baltic Fleet began maneuvers involving vessels and 313th Spetsnaz Special Forces frogmen out of the Baltiysk naval base.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 21 September the *SS-750* salvage ship, which is designed for specialized underwater operations and able to launch the AS-26 Priz-class mini-submarine left Baltiysk with its AIS inactive.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] *T-Online* additionally reported that on 22 September when the six Russian navy ships were operating in the area a Danish navy patrol boat and Swedish navy and air force were also present.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 18 April 2023, Danish newspaper *Dagbladet Information* cited a statement from the Danish Defence Command obtained via a freedom of information law request.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to this statement a Danish navy vessel took 112 military intelligence relevant photos of Russian vessels in the relevant area in September 2022, four days before the explosions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 27 April 2023 the Defence Command was again cited for a statement obtained by *Information* that confirmed T-Online's 25 March report that the *SS-750* salvage ship was among six Russian navy ships operating in the area.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Danish navy vessel had left port on the evening of 21 September and arrived the next morning at what would become the sabotage site, a location it had not patrolled for years.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] With its AIS transponder inactive it patrolled the area for hours, joined first by a surveillance aircraft from the Swedish Air Force and later by a corvette from the Swedish Navy.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] On 3 May 2023, an investigation by the Nordic public broadcasters DR, NRK, SVT, and Yle described "highly unusual" movements by ships thought to include Russian ships such as the tugboat SB-123, naval research vessel Sibiryakov, and another unspecified ship from the naval fleet.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] These ships had their transmitters turned off, and were reported to be in the area of the explosions between June up until 22 September 2022.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In May 2023, German newspaper *Süddeutsche Zeitung* reported that although the "[s]abotage last September has been linked to Russia", German investigators were sceptical as to whether the sabotage was carried out by Russian naval ships.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Later in May, *Der Spiegel* newspaper wrote that a "false flag" operation by Russia is considered extremely unlikely "among people familiar with the process".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In June 2023, the Biden administration publicly deflected questions regarding the perpetrators while Biden administration officials conceded in private that no conclusive evidence points to Moscow being behind the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In April 2023, German Defense Minister Boris Pistorius cautioned against making premature accusations as to who was behind the attack, suggesting that the alleged Ukrainian use of the 50-foot-sailing Yacht *Andromeda* might be a false flag operation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Commenting on these findings, member of the German Bundestag Roderich Kiesewetter said "Russia was involved in this attack".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In September 2023, Andreas Umland, analyst at the Stockholm Centre for Eastern European Studies, argued that the *Andromeda* was most likely a false flag created by Russia to implicate Ukraine.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Umland argued that Russia may have attempted "to kill two birds with one stone" and not only avoid that Gazprom should pay compensation for undelivered gas, but also to threaten the support from allies to Ukraine in its defense against the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Umland further argued that Ukraine had no interest in sabotaging the already "dead" pipelines, since Ukraine had other priorities with a war in their country.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to Umland, Russia had the strongest motives for the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Further, Umland saw a pattern in Russia's behavior, because after Russian-controlled forces had shot down Malaysia Airlines Flight 17, Russia tried to frame Ukraine for this crime as well.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Without providing evidence, Zaryn went on to state that *Andromeda*'s voyage had a "purely touristic character" with a crew "who were looking for fun" and where nobody seemed "to have anything close to military or sabotage-related training".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Kremlin has denied responsibility for the attack.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] These are four out of the six Russian naval vessels known to have operated in the area of the sabotage in the days before the explosions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Russia first accused the United Kingdom, and later the United States, of being responsible for the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] *Der Spiegel* reported that the United States Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) had warned the German government of possible sabotage to the pipelines weeks beforehand.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] *The New York Times* reported that the CIA had warned various European governments sometime in June.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The same sources said that at a second meeting the CIA signaled support for proceeding.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The CIA called the report "completely and utterly false".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to the Der Spiegel, the CIA later reversed course and warned the Ukrainians against proceeding, with a CIA representative at the Kyiv station raising the matter at the Ukrainian presidential office; the warnings were disregarded.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] At a United Nations Security Council meeting convened for the incident, Russian Federation representative Vasily Nebenzya suggested that the United States was involved in the pipeline damage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Deutsche Welle fact check concluded that the Russian claim "that an American helicopter was responsible for the gas leaks" is untenable and misleading.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The helicopter never flew along the pipeline and the gas leak areas were at least 9 and 30 kilometres (5.6 and 18.6 mi) away, respectively, from its flight path.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The post relied on a single anonymous source, whom Hersh described as having "direct knowledge of the operational planning." The White House responded to the story by calling it "utterly false and complete fiction".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs said that those allegations are "nonsense".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Subsequently, Hersh stated that the trail the German investigators were following on the "pro-Ukrainian group" that used a rented yacht was a false flag fabrication created by the CIA and fed to US and German outlets.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Swiss newspaper claimed this new information calls into question the assumption that a Ukrainian group was responsible for the sabotage and that investigations are continuing.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In March 2023, several international media outlets, citing anonymous sources, reported that a pro-Ukrainian group may have carried out the attack using the *Andromeda*, a 15.4-metre (50.6 ft) *Cruiser 50* sailing yacht from Bavaria Yachtbau.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] According to these reports, investigators found explosive residues on the *Andromeda* and that it had been rented by six people with professionally forged passports, for a Polish company with two Ukrainian owners.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The yacht is said have left Rostock on 6 September, briefly mooring at the port of Wiek and at the Danish island Christiansø, which is located 12 nautical miles (22 kilometres) from the explosion site.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Naval experts from Germany, Sweden and Denmark including lieutenant commander of the Danish navy and analyst at the Royal Danish Defence College J.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Riber scoffed at the idea that a 50-foot sailing yacht could be used for such a spectacular attack.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The naval experts point out that even with very skilled divers it would be extremely challenging for the crew of 6 to place at 262 feet (80 m) depth the explosives needed to create 2.5-Richter blasts.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The Danish and the Norwegian engineering newspapers *Ingeniøren* and *Teknisk Ukeblad* cited lieutenant commander J.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Riber, this time for several reasons why it is not credible that such a small vessel was used for the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The force of the explosion and the widely dispersed debris implies that several hundreds of kilograms of explosives were used, an amount that is impractical to transport with such a small sailboat.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Secondly, it is surprising that traces of explosives were found on the yacht, since in this case clearly no homemade explosive device was used.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Thirdly, accurately placing the explosives on the pipeline at 60–80 metres (200–260 ft) depth from a small surface vessel would be practically impossible.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The skepticism was shared by a named former chief analyst of the Danish Defence Intelligence Service now senior analyst in the Danish think tank *Europa*.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The naval officer speculated that a submarine was used to place the explosives and pointed out that a sonar-equipped submarine can, with relative ease, accurately place a naval bottom mine with 500 kilograms (1,100 lb) of explosives.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] As of April 2023, the yacht was being kept in a German dry dock for investigation.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In April 2023, German law enforcement officials suspected that the yacht *Andromeda* had been a decoy with other vessels actually used for the attack, consistent with the view of naval experts from Germany, Sweden and Denmark that the *Andromeda* was unsuitable for the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] As ambassador to the United Kingdom Zaluzhniy has in writing denied the allegations calling them a "mere provocation".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] A senior official of the Security Service of Ukraine also denied his government's involvement and reiterated that Zelenskyy "did not approve the implementation of any such actions on the territory of third countries and did not issue relevant orders".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] In August 2024 German TV station ARD conducted an experiment, hiring the very "Andromeda" yacht that was allegedly used in the sabotage and trying to replicate the scenario implicated by the investigators with professional divers.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The experiment failed, as the yacht was described as completely unsuitable for diving.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The TV then rented a professional diving ship and tried again, but concluded it would be "very difficult and dangerous" for two divers even using that vessel designed for diving.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The February 2026 *Der Spiegel* article said that the operation had been approved by then-commander-in-chief Valerii Zaluzhny but not by President Zelenskyy, whose office was not informed.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The report named a private Ukrainian citizen as the primary financier, covering approximately $300,000 in costs.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] An article published in *The Wall Street Journal* in June 2026 repeated the *Andromeda* theory, describing the attack in detail, including the use of lifting bags to lower the explosives, and repeating the claim that Zaluzhny had informed Zelenskyy of the attack.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Zelenskyy has denied his country was behind the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] Ukrainian presidential advisor Mykhailo Podolyak has also denied that Ukraine was behind the sabotage and instead blamed it on Russia.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p01] The lawmaker was also told that more than 450 kilograms (1,000 lb) of "military grade" explosives were used by the perpetrators.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] On 27 September 2022, European gas prices jumped 12 percent after news spread of the damaged pipelines, despite the fact that Nord Stream 1 had not delivered gas since August and Nord Stream 2 had never gone into service.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The Royal Danish Navy and Swedish Coast Guard sent ships to monitor the discharge and to establish an exclusion zone of 5 nautical miles (9.3 km; 5.8 mi) around the southernmost leak, and another of 7 nautical miles (13 km; 8.1 mi) around the other three, to keep other vessels away from danger.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Two of the ships were the Swedish *Amfitrite* and the Danish *Absalon*, which are specially designed to operate in contaminated environments such as gas clouds.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The US destroyer Paul Ignatius also contributed to maintaining the exclusion zone.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Vessels could lose buoyancy if they enter the gas plumes, and there might be a risk of leaked gas igniting over the water and in the air, but there were no risks associated with the leaks outside the exclusion zones.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] After the leaks, Norwegian authorities increased the security around their gas and oil infrastructure.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] On 5 October, Nord Stream 2 AG reported that Gazprom had begun pulling gas back out of the undamaged pipe for consumption in Saint Petersburg, reducing pipe pressure.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Infrastructure in the North Sea was being inspected for anomalies.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] On 11 January 2023, EU and NATO announced the creation of a task force on making their critical infrastructure more resilient to potential threats.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The leaks only affected the environment in the area where the gas plumes in the water column were located.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] A greater effect is likely to be the climate impact caused by the emission of 150 thousand tonnes (330 million pounds) of methane, a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The released volume is approximately 0.25% of the annual capacity of the pipelines, an amount nearly equal to the total release from all other sources of methane in a full year across Sweden.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The leaks caused Sweden's emissions to increase rather than decrease, risking an EU fine.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] A Danish official said these Nord Stream gas leaks could emit a CO2 equivalent of 14.6 million tonnes (32 billion pounds), similar to one third of Denmark's total annual greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The methane emissions from the leaks are equal to a few days of the emissions from regular fossil fuel production, and one third of the daily emissions from agriculture.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] However, the leaks set a record as the single largest discharge of methane, dwarfing all previously known leaks, such as the Aliso Canyon gas leak.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] A weather station in Norway logged an unprecedented 400 parts per billion (ppb) increase from a base level of 1800 ppb.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Equipment measured no increase in atmospheric methane at Bornholm.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Scientists from several European countries have analyzed the impact on marine ecosystems.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The shockwave is stated to have killed marine life within a radius of 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) and damaged the hearing of animals within 50 kilometres (31 mi).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] An estimated 250,000 tonnes (550 million pounds) of seafloor sediment containing lead and tributyltin used in anti-fouling paint have been lifted up.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Additionally, the area is contaminated from the dumping of ammunitions and chemical weapons.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] On 27 September 2022, Nord Stream AG, the operator of Nord Stream, said it was impossible to estimate when the infrastructure would be repaired.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] German authorities stated that unless they were rapidly repaired, the three damaged lines, both lines in Nord Stream 1 and line A in Nord Stream 2, were unlikely to ever become operational again due to corrosion caused by sea water.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] *The Washington Post* reported that the incidents are likely to put a permanent end to both Nord Stream projects.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] According to engineers, possible methods for the repair of the pipeline would include full-scale replacement of pipe segments and clamping of damaged sections.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] If carried out, repairs would be expected to last several months.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In February 2023, *The Times* reported that Russia had begun estimating repair costs, put at about $500 million.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In late January 2025, Danish authorities approved a plan to cut, plug and seal the broken pipe A during summer 2025.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Pipe A is estimated to still hold 9 million m3 of gas.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Pipe B is intact and has a pressure of 54 bar.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The bombings and subsequent underwater gas leaks resulted in reactions from a range of countries.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The day after the attack, the Prime Minister of Denmark Mette Frederiksen called the explosions deliberate and the leaks sabotage, while cautioning that it was not an attack on Denmark as they occurred in international waters.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In late 2022 August Hanning who until 2005 headed Germany's Federal Intelligence Service, said that Russia, Ukraine, Poland and Britain had a plausible interest in disabling the pipelines, as well as the US.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In August 2024 Hanning went on to say that he believes that there was an agreement between Zelenskyy and the Polish president Andrzej Duda to sabotage Nord Stream.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In August 2023, Roderich Kiesewetter, a member of the German Bundestag, tweeted that Russia must have been involved in the attack.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In 2025 Kiesewetter further called for closing the German investigation and instead focusing on investigating of Russian political influences in German political elites that led to construction of Nord Stream 1 following Russia's attack on Georgia and Nord Stream 2 following annexation of Crimea.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In a widely shared post on Twitter, Polish MEP and former foreign affairs and defence minister Radek Sikorski stated simply, "Thank you, USA", next to a photo of bubbling water above the pipeline damage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] We will bring an end to it" and went on to clarify that his working hypotheses regarding the motives and ability to perform the sabotage were of his own making.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Sikorski's post was criticized by many politicians and government officials.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Polish government spokesman Piotr Müller said it was harmful and served Russian propaganda.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] US State Department spokesman Ned Price characterized the idea of US involvement in the pipeline damage as "preposterous".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] *Der Spiegel* commented that Nord Stream 2 was already stopped entirely without explosives two days before Russia invaded Ukraine, and that exactly what Biden and Scholz had said would happen already had happened before the sabotage.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Sikorski deleted first the original and then all follow-up tweets several days later.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] In August 2024 after it became publicly known that Poland had failed to execute Germany's arrest warrant for a Nord Stream sabotage suspect prime minister of Poland Donald Tusk tweeted: "To all the initiators and patrons of Nord Stream 1 and 2.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The day after the attack, the Kremlin said that it did not rule out sabotage as a reason for the damage to the Nord Stream pipelines.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Dmitry Peskov, the Kremlin spokesman, said: "We cannot rule out any possibility right now.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Obviously, there is some sort of destruction of the pipe.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Before the results of the investigation, it is impossible to rule out any option." On 29 September, Russian President Vladimir Putin called the attack on the pipeline "an unprecedented act of international terrorism".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] On 2 February 2023, Russian foreign minister Sergei Lavrov said on Russian state television the US had direct involvement in the explosions intended to help preserve US global dominance.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The day after the attack, Sweden's Prime Minister Magdalena Andersson said that it likely was sabotage and also mentioned the detonations.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] On 12 April 2023, former US President Donald Trump, when asked who carried out the sabotage, said, "I don't want to get our country in trouble, so I won't answer it.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] But I can tell you who it wasn't was Russia." According to *Washington Post*, Trump "suggests that he knows something, but it's more likely just part of his effort to blame Biden for the war in Ukraine".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] The following day EU's foreign policy chief Josep Borrell said: "Any deliberate disruption of European energy infrastructure is utterly unacceptable and will be met with a robust and united response".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/2022-nord-stream-pipeline-sabotage-p02] Two days after the attack Secretary-General Jens Stoltenberg of NATO said the leaks were acts of sabotage and that he had discussed the protection of critical infrastructure within NATO with the Defence Minister of Denmark Morten Bødskov.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Since the passing of the Treaty of Union in 1707 which unified the Kingdom of Scotland with the Kingdom of England to the create the Kingdom of Great Britain, Scottish armed forces were merged with the English armed forces and remain part of the overall British Armed Forces.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] By 2020, Scotland's Regular Armed Forces personnel was expected to rise to 12,500, whilst the number of Trained Volunteer Reserves was projected to increase to 4,250.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In 2014, the total number of army personnel in Scotland was 17,300.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Scotland's geographical proximity to the North Atlantic and the High North make it an important component of the overall United Kingdom's defence and security.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Military bases in Scotland, including RAF Lossiemouth and HMNB Clyde are significant to the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO) northward defence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The country is home to 113 military establishments, including the United Kingdom's Trident nuclear power programme, Cape Wrath which is the only naval gunfire and firing range in the UK, the Benbecula live fire range for the Multiple Launch Rocket System and a NATO exercise area in Galloway Forest.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] From 2020, Scotland is home to one of only three Royal Navy main bases whereby all submarines of the Royal Navy are based in Scotland, one of the seven Adaptable Force Brigades of the British Army and a Royal Air Force fast jet main operating base.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In 1262, the Kingdom of Scotland invaded Norway beginning a war which lasted until 1266 and resulted in the Treaty of Perth.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Conflict between Scotland and Norway began over disagreements of who controlled the Hebrides off the coast of Scotland, however, Scotland later recognised Norwegian sovereignty over both Shetland and Orkney, purchasing the islands from Norway for a sum of 4,000 marks.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Under the terms of the Treaty of Perth, Norway acknowledged Scottish sovereignty over territory it had disputed with Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The payment was paid over the course of subsequent decades, until its cancellation as part of the agreement for the marriage of James III of Scotland and Margaret of Denmark, Queen of Scotland in 1469.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Before relinquishing its independence in 1707, the Kingdom of Scotland was an independent sovereign state and over the course of its history had engaged in various military battles with the Kingdom of England, particularly over the issue of the Wars of Scottish Independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The First War of Scottish Independence began following the English invasion of Scotland in 1296 until the *de jure* restoration of Scottish independence with the Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton in 1328, lasting a total of thirty-two years.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] *De facto* independence was established in 1314 at the Battle of Bannockburn.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The wars were caused by the attempts of the English kings to establish their authority over Scotland, while the Scots fought to keep English rule and authority out of Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] A second war between the Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England began in 1332 following the invasion of Scotland by Edward Balliol and lasted until 1357.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The King of England, Edward III, invaded Scotland in 1333 and besieged the important trading town of Berwick.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] A large Scottish army attempted to relieve it but was heavily defeated at the Battle of Halidon Hill.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Scotland had established an alliance with the Kingdom of France, known as the *Auld Alliance*.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] France was unhappy about an English expansion into Scotland and so covertly supported and financed the loyalists of David II of Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Allies of John Balliol fell out among themselves and Balliol lost control of most of Scotland by late 1334.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In early 1335, the French attempted to broker a peace but failed.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Further French-sponsored peace talks failed in 1336 and by May 1337, King Philip VI of France engineered a clear break between France and England, starting the Hundred Years' War.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Prior to the Treaty of Union 1707, the Kingdom of Scotland's army was the Scots Army and their navy was the Royal Scots Navy.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] At the Restoration in 1660 the Privy Council of Scotland established a force of several infantry regiments and a few troops of horse to act as a standing army.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] There were also attempts to found a national militia of 20,000 foot and 2,000 horse on the English model.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The standing army was mainly employed in suppressing Covenanter rebellions and the guerrilla war waged by the Cameronians in the East.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In addition, a "Foote Company of Highland Men" was raised and three troops of Scots Dragoons in 1678.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Another three were added to make The Royal Regiment of Scots Dragoons in 1681, by which point they were already mounted on grey horses that would give them their name of the Royal Scots Greys.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] On the eve of the Glorious Revolution the standing army in Scotland was about 3,000 men in various regiments and another 268 veterans in the major garrison towns, at an annual cost of about £80,000.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Under the terms of the Treaty of Union between the Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England, the Scots Army was integrated with the English army.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] It became part of the British Armed Forces.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Following a referendum on devolution for Scotland in 1997, a Scottish Parliament was re–established together with an executive which operate under the Scotland Act 1998.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Defence and national security remain reserved matters under the Scotland Act 1998 which mean they are the overall responsibility of the UK parliament and reserved matters are set out in schedule 5 of the Scotland Act 1998.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The UK Government claims that Scotland's geography, and military capabilities is essential for the UK and NATO's defence and security in the North Atlantic and the High North.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The UK Government pledged to increase the regular armed forces to 12,500 by 2020, which has not been met and has thus been criticised by the Scottish Government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scottish government argues that Westminster's commitment to nuclear weapons has weakened other aspects of Scottish defence, and that Trident renewal will reduce funding for conventional equipment and the number of service personnel.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] They also claim that "cost overruns are endemic and major projects have been significantly delayed" and use the example of two aircraft carriers built before the availability of aircraft for them.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The reserve battalions include the 52nd Lowland Volunteers, 6th Battalion (6 SCOTS), the 51st Highland Volunteers, 7th Battalion (7 SCOTS), the Band of the Royal Regiment of Scotland and the Lowland Band of the Royal Regiment of Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Royal Scots Borderers (1 SCOTS) was disbanded in 2021, with its personnel forming the 1st Battalion of the newly formed Ranger Regiment (1 RANGERS).
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scots Guards is one of the five Foot Guards regiments of the British Army.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Its origins are as the personal bodyguard of King Charles I of England and Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Whilst defence and security remain a reserved matter to the UK Government under the terms of the Scotland Act 1998, the Scottish Government does have a role to play in terms of supporting Scotland's military personnel and veterans.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scottish Government advocates that it "aims to put the needs of the armed forces and veterans community at the forefront of policy thinking, development and delivery" as it "recognises the sacrifice of the armed forces, veterans and their families".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] A junior ministerial post was created in the Scottish Government under First Minister Humza Yousaf.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Minister for Veterans provides an update to the Scottish Parliament annually on the governments work relating to community support for Scotland's personnel and veterans.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Minister for Veterans is responsible for ensuring Scottish Government support is in place for veterans and currently serving personnel.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In the event of Scotland regaining its independence, the Scottish Government would establish a Scottish Armed Forces and work with the UK Government for the transfer of defence personnel to the newly established Scottish armed forces.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scottish Government would conduct a Defence and Security Review to examine the components required for defence and security of an independent Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scottish Government has long advocated for the removal of nuclear weapons from Scotland, such as the Trident nuclear programme.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] It is proposed the make up of the Scottish Armed Forces would include land, sea and air components which the creation of a new Joint Forces Headquarters would oversee.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scottish Security and Intelligence Agency would serve as the security and intelligence body of the Scottish Government.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scottish Government advocates that an independent Scotland join the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO) and would begin discussions and negotiations with NATO and its member states on Scotland's accession.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] An independent Scotland would commit 2% of its Gross Domestic Product (GDP) towards defence spending in accordance with the commitment from NATO to invest in defence capabilities.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Additionally, the Scottish Government supports membership of the European Union (EU) for an independent Scotland and, as such, would participate in the Common Security and Defence Policy of the EU.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Following independence, the Scottish Government pledges the continuation of a robust and strong partnership between the Scottish and British Armed Forces, along with the Republic of Ireland, towards the security and protection of the wider British Isles.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] As of April 2021, the Regular Armed Forces in Scotland included 3,790 in the Army, 4,270 in the Navy and 2,060 in the Air Force.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The UK government views the UK's defence as being "stronger and safer" with cooperative Scottish participation in the combined defence and security of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The UK government claims for 2021/22 that defence spending per capita was £370 in Scotland and £310 for the whole of the UK.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In 2023, then First Minister Humza Yousaf said that an independent Scotland would aim to maintain 2% GDP defence spending to meet the NATO target.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The centre of Army operations in Scotland is Leuchars Station in Fife, the base for the Royal Scots Dragoon Guards, which also houses Royal Engineers, Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers**,** and Royal Military Police units.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Robin Lindsay is the Military Secretary and General Officer Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In 2021, UK Defence Secretary Ben Wallace made a commitment that the number of battalions stationed in Scotland would increase from six to seven units and that the Army in Scotland would be a "greater proportion of the Army than today".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] He also said that Kinloss and Leuchars bases would be expanded.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Redford Barracks is set to close in 2029 and Fort George is set to close in 2032 as part of the UK government's Future Soldier plan.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Black Watch battalion will relocate from Fort George barracks to Leuchars (both in Scotland) in 2029.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] This would mean closure of Fort George in 2029 rather than 2032 as originally planned and the return of the Black Watch to the traditional recruiting area of Tayside.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] His Majesty's Naval Base, Clyde, commonly known as Faslane, houses the nuclear-armed Vanguard 15 class submarines that form the "At-Sea Nuclear Deterrent".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The base also houses the Astute Class of attack submarines and a frigate acting as a Towed Array Patrol ship operates that protect Trident-equipped submarines and perform anti-submarine activities.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Due to retreat of arctic ice, it is possible that maritime activity in the High North will increase with a further emphasis on RN activities from Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] This is made more likely by Russian emphasis on arctic naval activity.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Scottish government and a cross-party majority in the Scottish Parliament is opposed to having nuclear weapons in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In the event of Scottish independence, which is supported by the Scottish government, the nuclear programme will be moved out of Scotland "at pace".
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The SNP have claimed that Scotland spends £180m annually on Trident alone, and so £180m would be saved each year with the removal of Trident and independence.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] In the event of Scottish independence, the MOD of the UK's preferred option would be to move the at-sea nuclear deterrent base to Devonport naval base in Plymouth.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The UK government has no plans to move Trident otherwise.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] RAF assets in Scotland operate in defence of the North Atlantic and the High North via; surveillance, anti-submarine warfare and Quick Reaction Alert jets from Lossiemouth base, which is the primary air base in Scotland.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Air Officer Scotland is Air-Vice Marshall Ross Paterson.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Surveillance of the Greenland-Iceland-UK gap (GIUK gap) also occurs from Lossiemouth which contributes to Iceland's policing.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The P-8A Poseidon maritime patrol aircraft is used in the GIUK gap and for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Norwegian P-8As also use facilities at Lossiemouth, and the RAF also uses Norwegian bases.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] The Norwegian Ambassador says this provides cost savings and operational flexibility.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] Twice a year Exercise Joint Warrior utilises the Royal Navy, Royal Marines, Royal Air Force and British Army, in cooperation with forces from 13 other countries in order to test NATO's 'Very High Readiness' forces.
[src:armed-forces-in-scotland/armed-forces-in-scotland] As of 2017, there were around 230,000 veterans living in Scotland.
